vocabList.etym: Borrowed in the 17th century, and provided with a paragogic -t, from French (vin) sec (literally “dry wine”), which is also the original sense in German. The sense “sparkling wine” is believed to originate from an anecdote in 19th-century Berlin. The actor Ludwig Devrient supposedly ordered a bottle of wine using the phrase “Bring [er] mir Sekt, Schurke!”, based on the German translation of the line “Give me a cup of sack, rogue!” from Shakespeare’s Henry IV. He was served sparkling wine, his usual order, and this sense was given to the word Sekt when the phrase and anecdote caught on.

From Middle High German lest, a contraction of lezzest, from Old High German lezzist (also lazzōst), itself superlative of laz (cognate to English late). The modern German form with -tz- is of northern origin; two separate origins have probably met in it: Firstly, there is a general tendency in some Central German dialects of inserting -t- before comparative and superlative endings. (Compare for this, for example, Ripuarian fröh → fröhter, fröhtste). Secondly, Middle Low German lest, contracted superlative of lat (“late”), had a regular or regularized variant letst, which is very rare in writing, but may have been more common in spoken dialects. (Compare modern German Low German lättst.) Related forms are Dutch laatst and lest, English latest and last, Luxembourgish lescht, Hunsrik letst.

German Park remained sporadic, however, until it was reinforced (or borrowed anew) from modern French parc and English park from the late 17th century on. Probably borrowed from Old Dutch *gilukki as part of the Flemish knight culture; compare Middle Dutch gelucke (1240), whence modern Dutch geluk. (The fact that the word is attested in High German before Dutch must be disregarded in view of the minimal attestation of Old Dutch as a whole.)
vocabList.usage:
Das größte Glück im Leben ist es, geliebt zu werden.
The greatest joy in life is to be loved.

vocabList.etym: From Late Middle High German freywillic (1370s), but common chiefly since the 16th century. By surface analysis, frei (“free”) +‎ willig (“willing”), perhaps after freier Wille (“free will”). Compare Dutch vrijwillig (1390s).
foto- +‎ -graf
form +‎ -ell
From Fach (“field of study, subject”) +‎ Hochschule (“college, university”).
From Middle High German vach, from Old High German fah, from Proto-West Germanic *fak, from Proto-Germanic *faką.

From Middle High German etwā, contraction of etewā (also eteswā), from Old High German edde(s)hwār (“somewhere”). For the first component compare etlich, etwas; the second is wo (“where”). A related formation was Middle High German ete(s)wanne, in which the second component is wann (“when”). It yielded modern etwan, which was displaced by the 19th century.
vocabList.usage:
Das Gebäude ist etwa 30 Meter hoch.
The height of the building is approximately 30 metres.

vocabList.etym: Eltern (“parents”) +‎ Abend (“evening”)
From Bund +‎ -es- +‎ Land, the former related to binden (“bind”). In a literal sense: 'one of several lands bound to another' or more simply 'allied country'.
Ca. 1800, from bio- +‎ -logie.

From Middle High German berāten, from Old High German birātan, from Proto-West Germanic *birādan. Equivalent to be- +‎ raten. Cognate with obsolete English berede (“to advise”) and beread (“to inform, counsel, plan”) and Dutch beraden.
begrüßen +‎ -ung
From Middle High German angest, from Old High German angust, from Proto-Germanic *angustiz.

vocabList.usage:
Natürlich ist jeder Mensch und jede Situation anders.
Of course every person and every situation are different.

vocabList.etym: vorbei- +‎ kommen
vocabList.usage:
Möchten Sie auf einen Kaffee vorbeikommen?
Would you like to drop by for coffee?

vocabList.etym: From versichern.
From vermeiden (“avoid”) +‎ -ung.
ver- +‎ Abschied (“parting, farewell”) +‎ -en

vocabList.definition: to support, to assist, to help, to aid
vocabList.etym: unter- +‎ stützen
vocabList.usage:
Sein Onkel unterstützt ihn bis heute finanziell.
His uncle supports him financially until today.

vocabList.etym: über +‎ lasten
Compound of Tee +‎ Licht.
From Rettung +‎ -s- +‎ Wagen.
From mehrfach +‎ Steckdose.
Unadapted borrowing from English marketing
Borrowed from English laptop.

From Middle High German kraft, from Old High German kraft, from Proto-West Germanic *kraftu, from Proto-Germanic *kraftuz (strength, power).
Cognate with Dutch kracht, Low German Kracht, English craft, Danish kraft.
vocabList.usage:
Er hat keine Kraft mehr.
He has no more power.

vocabList.etym: Kopie +‎ -ieren.
Kennzeichen (“characteristic”) +‎ -en
Compound of Kabel (“cable”) +‎ Salat (“salad”).
From Middle High German hinvarn, from Old High German hinafaran. Equivalent to hin- +‎ fahren.
From heraus- +‎ suchen. This etymology is incomplete. You can help Wiktionary by elaborating on the origins of this term.

From Middle High German gesunt, from Old High German gisunt, from Proto-West Germanic *gasund, a prefixed form of *sund, from Proto-Germanic *sundaz. Cognates include Bavarian gsund, Dutch gezond, English sound.
From late Middle High German [Term?].
From Feuer (“fire”) +‎ löschen (“to extinguish”) +‎ -er.
From einweisen +‎ -ung.
From Middle High German diuticlīche (adverb), equivalent to deuten +‎ -lich.
From Middle High German danken, from Old High German dankōn. Compare Dutch danken, English thank, Danish takke.
vocabList.usage:
Peter hat Michaela mit einem großen Blumenstrauß gedankt.
Peter thanked Michaela with a big bouquet.

vocabList.etym: From Buch (“book”) +‎ Haltung (“keeping”).
Brand +‎ Bekämpfung
Middle High German bewarn, from Old High German biwarōn, from Proto-Germanic *biwarōną. By surface analysis, be- +‎ wahren, see the latter for more. Cognate with English beware.
be- +‎ tätigen
From bereit +‎ stellen.
From Middle High German bereite, from Old High German bireiti, reiti; from Proto-West Germanic *raidī, from the Proto-Germanic base *raidaz (“ready”). Cognate with English ready, Vilamovian byrat.
From Arbeit +‎ -s- +‎ Vertrag.
anrufen +‎ -er
From Middle High German aneruof, from Old High German anaruof, anahruof. By surface analysis, deverbal from anrufen (literally “calling, ringing”).
From Middle High German abteilunge. Equivalent to abteilen +‎ -ung.
Borrowed from Italian zucchini, plural of zucchino.
zu- +‎ bereiten

Formed from the noun Vegetarier (“vegetarian”) +‎ -isch
From older Vegetarianer, a borrowing from English vegetarian.
Vanille +‎ Eis
Unadapted borrowing from English toaster.

Borrowed from English tattoo. The rather common pronunciation with initial stress perhaps partly from a mistakenly assumed English form, but at least reinforced by the related words tätowieren, Tätowierung (both with unstressed -o- and often secondary stress on -ä-).
Borrowed from English steak, from Old Norse steik.
Borrowed from English snack.
From Middle High German silber, from Old High German silbar, from Proto-West Germanic *silubr. Cognate with Dutch zilver, English silver.
Borrowed from English shorts.
Schuh +‎ Größe
From Middle High German schrei, schrē, from Old High German screi. First attested in the 9th century. Cognate with Hunsrik Schreu. Ultimately from the root of schreien (“to shout, cry out”).

A borrowing from German Low German Snurrbaart, equivalent to schnurren (“to purr”) +‎ Bart (“beard”), thus the "purring beard", perhaps owing to its tendency to rustle when its owner speaks or "purrs", or perhaps due to its resemblance to the whiskers of a purring cat. Compare Schnurrhaar (“whisker”).
From schauen (“to look, to watch”) +‎ Fenster (“window”).

From Middle High German schouwen, from Old High German scouwōn, from Proto-Germanic *skawwōną (“to look, see, watch”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewh₁- (“to heed, look, feel, take note of”). Cognate with Old English scēawian (“to look at, examine, show”). Compare English show.
Schaf +‎ -s- +‎ Käse
Polizei (“police”) +‎ -ist (“-ist”)
Borrowed from French parfumerie.
From Middle High German ōrrinc, from Old High German ōrring, from Proto-West Germanic *auʀahring, equivalent to Ohr (“ear”) +‎ Ring (“ring”). Cognate with English earring.
Mode +‎ Schmuck
Mineral (“mineral”) +‎ Wasser (“water”)
vocabList.usage: stilles (Mineral-)Wasser ― still water

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German mūs, from Old High German mūs, from Proto-Germanic *mūs. Doublet of Mouse.
vocabList.usage:
Ich sehe ein Mäuslein, die sich in der Wand versteckt.
I see a little mouse hiding in that wall.

vocabList.etym: Unadapted borrowing from English make-up.
Liebling +‎ -s- +‎ Farbe
Küche (“kitchen”) +‎ Gerät (“appliance”)
Kopf +‎ Hörer
Borrowed from French compliment.
From French carré +‎ -iert and Karo.
Borrowed from New Latin camera obscūra (“dark chamber”), from Latin camera (“chamber, bedchamber”). Doublet of Kammer and Kamurke.
Compound of Haut +‎ Pflege.
haupt- +‎ Gericht

vocabList.definition: Greek, Grecian, from or related to Greece
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German kriechisch, from Old High German chriehhisc. By surface analysis, Grieche +‎ -isch.
From Middle High German golt, from Old High German gold, from Proto-West Germanic *golþ, from Proto-Germanic *gulþą.
ge- +‎ Streifen +‎ -t
From French frit +‎ -ieren.
From Latin phantasticus, with assimilation to native suffix -isch. By surface analysis, Fantast (“fantasist, dreamer”) +‎ -isch.
From ein- (“one, uni-”) +‎ farbig (“color”).
From Ehe +‎ Paar.
17th century, from French égal.
duschen (“to shower”) +‎ Gel (“gel”)
From Middle High German dünne, from Old High German dunni, from Proto-West Germanic *þunnī.

From Middle High German tuft, from Old High German duft, thuft, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, be obscured”) (DWDS); cognate with Danish duft (“fragrance”) and possibly Ancient Greek τῠφλός (tŭphlós, “blind”).[1] The Middle High German t- is an irregular hardening (compare tausend) that was undone in modern German.
vocabList.usage:
Er bemerkte einen süßlichen Duft als er die Küche betrat.
He noticed a sweet aroma as he entered the kitchen.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ding, from Old High German thing, from Proto-West Germanic *þing. Compare Low German ding, Dutch ding, English thing, Danish ting.

From Middle High German diep, Old High German diob, from Proto-West Germanic *þeub, from Proto-Germanic *þeubaz. Cognate with Old Norse þýfð, Old English þēof, Dutch dief, English thief, Gothic 𐌸𐌹𐌿𐍆𐍃 (þiufs).[1]
From dar- +‎ in
From Curry (“curry”) +‎ Wurst (“sausage”).
Derived from French champignon (“mushroom”).
Unadapted borrowing from English camping.

17th century, for “to swing, waver” (of the clapper of a bell), iterative formation from onomatopoeic bim-bam-bum for the sound of a bell; compare bimmeln (“to ring”). From this Low German bummeln (18th c.) in the contemporary sense. Related with baumeln (likely an alteration after Baum) and Bommel (“bobble”).[1]

Borrowed from French blond, from Frankish *blund, from Proto-Germanic *blundaz, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰlendʰ-. The earlier borrowing Middle High German blunt was rare and had no continuation in early modern German.
vocabList.usage:
Blonde Haare sind vor allem bei den Völkern germanischer und slawischer Abstammung verbreitet.
Blond hair is primarily common among the peoples of Germanic and Slavic descent.

vocabList.etym: baden (“to bathe”) +‎ Sachen (“things, stuff”)
vocabList.usage:
Viele Hotelgäste gehen nach dem Essen direkt zum Strand, einige haben schon ihre Badesachen an.
Many hotel guests go directly to the beach after eating, some already have their swimwear on.

vocabList.etym: Mid-19th-century borrowing from English baby. The use as a term of endearment is a later borrowing from late-20th-century pop culture; it remains far more common in pop music than in real life.
Unadapted borrowing from French aubergine. Doublet of Melanzani.
Compound of Apfel +‎ Schorle.

From Middle High German anehaben, anhaben, from Old High German anahabēn, from Proto-West Germanic *anahabbjan, from Proto-Germanic *anahabjaną. Equivalent to an- +‎ haben. Compare Dutch aanhebben, English have on, Gothic 𐌰𐌽𐌰𐌷𐌰𐌱𐌰𐌽 (anahaban).
vocabList.usage:
Er hat keine Sandalen an.
He doesn’t have sandals on.

vocabList.etym: From er- +‎ möglich +‎ -en.
From Middle High German richten, from Old High German rihten, from Proto-West Germanic *rihtijan (“to right”). Cognate with English right.

vocabList.definition: to turn something so as to cook or roast it from both sides
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wenden, from Old High German wenten, from Proto-West Germanic *wandijan.
From überzeugen (“to convince”) +‎ -ung (“-ing”).
Univerbation from earlier adverbial genitive ebenen Falls (literally “just the same case”).

From Middle High German verbieten, from Old High German firbiotan, from Proto-West Germanic *furibeudan, from Proto-Germanic *furibeudaną. Equivalent to ver- +‎ bieten. Compare Dutch verbieden, Low German verbeden, English forbid, Danish forbyde, Swedish förbjuda, Gothic 𐍆𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌱𐌹𐌿𐌳𐌰𐌽 (faurbiudan).
vocabList.usage:
Ich verbiete Ihnen, in diesem Ton mit meiner Frau zu sprechen.
I forbid you to talk in that tone of voice with my wife.

vocabList.etym: be- +‎ zweifeln

Compound of aller (genitive plural of alle (“all”)) +‎ Dings (genitive singular of Ding (“thing”)) (compare schlechterdings). Before the 19th century, the full form aller Dinge (“of all things”), with the plural Dinge, was used.
vocabList.usage:
Es wird allerdings die Vermutung ausgesprochen...
It is, however, conjectured...

vocabList.definition: to load onto, to load up, to charge
vocabList.etym: auf +‎ laden
From fähig (“capable, able”) +‎ -keit.

From Middle High German pfanne, from Old High German phanna, from Proto-West Germanic *pannā, from Proto-Germanic *pannǭ, from Late Latin panna, from Latin patina (“bowl, platter”). Doublet of Patina.
Alster +‎ Wasser, after the tributary of the Elbe River.
Of uncertain origin. Attested since the 15th century. Several etymologies have been proposed.[1]
verfügen +‎ -bar
verstehen +‎ -nis
From Middle High German vegen, from Old High German fegōn, from Proto-West Germanic *fegōn.

Coined in the 15th century after the model of wahnwitzig which uses as its first part the word wahn, which came from Old High German wan "missing, empty", which came from Proto-Germanic *wanaz. Not cognate with Wahn. Cognate with English wane.
vocabList.usage:
Sind Sie wahnsinnig?
Are you insane?

vocabList.etym: un- +‎ berechenbar
From Middle High German māz, from Old High German māza, from Proto-West Germanic *mātu. Compare Dutch maat (“size, measure”), Old English met (“measure, amount, limit”). More at mete.
vocabList.usage:
Ehrlichkeit ist das wahre Maß eines Mannes.
Honesty is the true measure of a man.

vocabList.etym: From gemein +‎ -schaft. Cognate to German Low German Gemeenschopp (Gemeenschop), Middle Low German Gemeinschopp (in 16th century, used by Joachimus Magdeburgius).
Außenseite +‎ -er
From Middle High German niderslahen, from Old High German nidarslahan. Equivalent to nieder- +‎ schlagen.

From Middle High German īseren, īserīn, from Old High German īsarnīn, from Proto-Germanic *īsarnīnaz. Equivalent to Eiser (“iron”), older variant of Eisen +‎ -en. Now reanalysable as Eisen (“iron”) +‎ -ern, but historically eisern is itself one of the words that contributed to the development of this extended suffix -ern (see there).
From mit- +‎ Gefühl. Cognate with Dutch medegevoel.
From horchen.
vocabList.usage:
Sie gehorchten ihren Eltern nicht.
They didn't obey their parents.

vocabList.etym: ur- +‎ Sünde
ge- +‎ schwätzen
Univerbation of so +‎ genannt.
schwach +‎ -e
From Middle High German vergeben, from Old High German fargeban, from Proto-Germanic *fragebaną. Analyzable as ver- +‎ geben. Cognate with Dutch vergeven, English forgive, Icelandic fyrirgefa.
Compare Dutch oneerbiedig.
um- +‎ krempeln
From Middle High German gewaltec, from Old High German giwaltīg, equivalent to Gewalt +‎ -ig.
erdenken +‎ -lich
From Middle High German zuobringen, from Old High German zuobringan. Equivalent to zu- +‎ bringen.
From Middle High German verræter.
From versagen +‎ -er.

From Treue +‎ -los.
Niedertracht +‎ -ig. Also analyzable as nieder- +‎ -trächtig.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German beliegen, from Old High German biliogan, from Proto-West Germanic *bileugan. Equivalent to be- +‎ lügen.

vocabList.definition: to set against, to make a stand against

vocabList.etym: From Schupp (“push”) +‎ -s (“intensive nominal ending”). Schupp (15th c.) is deverbal from northern Middle High German and Middle Low German schuppen, from Proto-Germanic *skuppōną, intensive form of *skeubaną, whence German schieben and English shove. See schubsen for more.
er- +‎ folgen
vocabList.usage:
Der Angriff Steiners ist nicht erfolgt.
Steiner's attack did not occur.

vocabList.etym: Borrowed from French masser, probably from Arabic مَسَّ (massa, “to touch”), or from Portuguese amassar. The Arabic verb was, in French, associated with and perhaps reinforced by unrelated Ancient Greek μάσσειν (mássein, “to knead”), but direct derivation from this latter is now considered unlikely.

vocabList.definition: attack, offensive, strike, assault, onslaught, raid, offence
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German angrif, anegrif, from Old High German *anagrif, from Proto-West Germanic *anagripi, equivalent to an- +‎ Griff. Related to German angreifen.

vocabList.definition: to reach, get to, end up in
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gelangen, from Old High German gilangōn, synchronically analyzed as an ablaut formation from gelingen (“to succeed”) (Duden).
vocabList.usage:
Das kurze Video gelangte in falsche Hände.
The short video ended up in the wrong hands.

vocabList.etym: From Old High German in zuiskēn, from Old High German zuiski, from Proto-Germanic *twiskaz (“twofold, double”), from Proto-Indo-European *dwís (“twice, doubly; in two”).
vocabList.usage:
die Schere zwischen Arm und Reich
the gap between the poor and rich

vocabList.definition: to break something in two [auxiliary haben]
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German durchbrechen, from Old High German duruhbrehhan, from Proto-West Germanic *þuruhbrekan; analyzable as durch (“through”) +‎ brechen (“to break”).
From Middle High German vīant, from Old High German fīand, fīant, from Proto-West Germanic *fijand, from Proto-Germanic *fijandz.
vocabList.usage:
Er ist mein größter Feind
He is my greatest enemy.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German bevel, synchronically analyzed as a deverbal noun from befehlen (“to order, command”). Compare also Dutch bevel.

From Italian tasto (“key”), from the verb tastare, from Vulgar Latin *tastāre (“to touch, feel”), from *taxitāre, from Latin taxāre (“to touch sharply”), from tangere (“to touch”). Related with older German tasten, which is from the same Latin verb through Old French.
From Konto +‎ Auszug.
From Middle High German herūzkomen. Equivalent to heraus- +‎ kommen.
From Fehler +‎ Meldung.
From auszahlen +‎ -ung.

vocabList.etym: aus- (“out”) +‎ wählen (“pick, choose, select”).  Compare English pick out.
aus- +‎ drucken
From Middle High German abebruch. By surface analysis, deverbal from abbrechen.

A Central and Low German verb, from Middle Low German klappen, probably from Proto-West Germanic *klappōn, from Proto-Germanic *klappōną. Cognate with Dutch klappen, English clap, Old High German klapfō (“clapping sound”). Also related with German klaffen (“to be wide open”).
From ein +‎ -sam, probably on the model of gemeinsam.
From zu- (“to, at”) +‎ gleich (“equal, same, alike”).

vocabList.etym: 16th century, originally in the longer form bissolang, a univerbation of bis (“until”) +‎ so (“so”) +‎ lang (“long”). The word was at first chiefly restricted to vernacular High German in northern Germany. It established itself more widely in the 19th century, but remains rare in Austria, Switzerland and South Tyrol.
da (“there”) +‎ gegen.

vocabList.definition: accessories, fittings, paraphernalia, equipment, supplies, belongings
vocabList.etym: 17th century, northern alteration of the above form, itself from Middle High German zuogehœr(d)e, under influence of the equivalent Middle Low German tôbehö̂re, literally “to-belongings”, thus “that which belongs to something else”. The northern behören for gehören see also in Behörde; compare Dutch behoren.
From the obsolete verb bereichen (“to extend; to cover”, literally “bereach”).
From Middle High German stætec (“firm, constant, stable”), Old High German stāti;[1] analyzable as stet +‎ -ig.
From Middle High German anevart, from Old High German anafart. By surface analysis, deverbal from anfahren.
Verwendung (“use”) +‎ -s- +‎ Zweck (“purpose”)
vermieten (“to rent”) +‎ -er (“-er”)
From über- +‎ weisen.
vocabList.usage:
Sie müssen den Betrag sofort überweisen.
You have to transfer the amount immediately.

vocabList.etym: Ca. 1500, from Latin rata, perhaps through Italian rata and/or Middle French rate.
mahnen +‎ -ung
Last +‎ Schrift

vocabList.definition: to take care, to look after
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German kumbern, derived from the noun kumber, probably from Old French *combre (“obstruction, barrier”), itself probably from Gaulish. See Kummer for more.
vocabList.usage:
Wer kümmert sich um die Ausbildung der Lehrlinge?
Who takes care of training the interns?

vocabList.etym: Konto +‎ Stand

From Middle High German enphāhen, from Old High German intvāhan, from Proto-Germanic *andfanhaną. Equivalent to emp- +‎ fangen and further ent- +‎ fangen. Cognate with Dutch ontvangen, Old Saxon antfāhan.
ein- (“in-”) +‎ zahlen (“to pay”)
From Dauer +‎ Auftrag.
From Middle High German īngeben, from Old High German ingeban. Equivalent to ein- +‎ geben. Compare Scots ingive.

Borrowed from Middle Low German beschênigen (14th c.), extended form of beschênen, from be- +‎ Proto-West Germanic *skainijan (“to make appear”). This latter verb is a causative of *skīnan, whence German scheinen (“to shine, appear”). It was borrowed along the Lower Rhine in the 15th century and fully established itself in High German during the 16th. Due to the merger of West Germanic ai and ī, it appears to be derived as be- +‎ Schein +‎ -ig +‎ -en. In truth, the noun Schein is closely related, but does not underlie directly.
From Middle High German anelāzen, from Old High German anelāzan. Equivalent to an- +‎ lassen.

vocabList.definition: to come off, come loose, to wear off, to be deducted
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German abegān, from Old High German abagān. Equivalent to ab- +‎ gehen.
ab- +‎ buchen
From Middle High German ūzvüeren, from Old High German ūzfuoren. By surface analysis, aus (“out”) +‎ führen (“to lead”). Compare Dutch uitvoeren.
vocabList.usage:
Heute früh habe ich meinen Hund ausgeführt.
I took my dog for a walk this morning.

vocabList.etym: From the verb betragen.
Inherited from Middle High German betragen and independent formations from be- +‎ tragen
vocabList.usage:
Die Atommasse wird auf eine Skala bezogen, auf der die Masse des Atoms 6 12 C {\displaystyle _{6}^{12}\mathrm {C} } 12 u beträgt.
The atom mass is related to a scale, in which the mass of the atom 6 12 C {\displaystyle _{6}^{12}\mathrm {C} } amounts to 12 u.

vocabList.etym: From tätig +‎ -keit.
From Middle High German *ersūfen, from Old High German irsūfan. Equivalent to er- +‎ saufen.
fernsehen +‎ -er
herunter- +‎ fahren
From Middle High German geil, from Old High German geil, from Proto-West Germanic *gail ("wanton, lustful"), from Proto-Germanic *gailaz ("frothing, arrogant, tempestuous, violent, wanton").
erleben +‎ -nis

From Middle High German wels, from Old High German *wals, *walis, from Proto-West Germanic *hwaliʀ, from Proto-Germanic *hwalaz, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kʷálos (“sheatfish”). Cognate with German Low German Wels (“catfish”), Dutch wels (“catfish”), Old High German walira (“whale”), German Wal (“whale”).
bei- +‎ bringen.
vocabList.usage:
Dann wird den Kindern das Lesen beigebracht.
Then the children are taught reading.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wec, from Old High German weg, from Proto-West Germanic *weg. Cognate with Dutch weg, Afrikaans weg, English way.
vocabList.usage:
Der Wald kann gefährlich sein, also bleib auf dem Weg.
The forest can be dangerous, so stay on the path.

vocabList.etym: Ca. 1600, deverbal from nach +‎ richten. Compare Dutch naricht.
vocabList.usage:
Die Nachricht von seinem Tod hat mich tief erschüttert.
The news of his death shocked me deeply.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German mittel, from Old High German mittil (akin to Old Saxon middil), from Proto-Germanic *midlą, *midilą, *medalą (“middle”), *midil-. Compare Dutch middel, English middle. See also Mitte.
From fern (“far away”) +‎ Verkehr (“traffic”).
Univerbation of ob +‎ wohl, from the older use of ob as a conditional and concessive conjunction, reinforced with an adverb. Compare obgleich, obschon, obzwar and also gleichwohl.
vocabList.usage:
Frau Anna, unsere Empfangsdame, flirtet mit Patienten, obwohl sie Mutter von drei Kindern ist.
Ms. Anna, our receptionist, flirts with patients, although she is the mother of three children.

vocabList.etym: Univerbation of trotz +‎ dem. Compare Middle High German tratz, traz, truz (“anyhow, nevertheless”).
vocabList.usage:
Ich verstehe deine Sichtweise. Trotzdem bin ich anderer Meinung.
I understand your point of view. Nevertheless, I have a different opinion.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German kleit, from Old High German *kleid, from Proto-Germanic *klaiþą, from Proto-Indo-European *gleyt-. Cognate with Dutch kleed, Low German Kleid, English cloth. Possibly related to klettern, Klette, Klei.
From Middle High German tol, from Old High German tol, from Proto-West Germanic *dol, from Proto-Germanic *dulaz (“dazed, foolish, crazy, stupid”).
From herstellen +‎ -er.
From sonder- (“special”) +‎ Angebot (“offer”).
From Middle High German urloup. Related to erlauben. Cognate with English leave (“time off, permission to be away”).
From Late Middle High German koffer, from Middle Dutch coffer, from Old French cofre.
From Middle High German sō, from Old High German sō, from Proto-West Germanic *swā, from Proto-Germanic *swa, *swē, compare with Old Dutch so and Dutch zo.
From Middle High German nie, from Old High German nio.
From Middle High German selten, selden, from Old High German seltan, from Proto-West Germanic *seldanā.
From Middle High German ofte, oft, uft, from Old High German ofta, ofto, oftu, from Proto-Germanic *ufta, *uftō (“often”). Cognate with Dutch oft, English oft and often.
From the noun Mal (“time”). Partly shortened from einmal, which is also derived from the noun.
vocabList.usage:
sechs mal sieben ist zweiundvierzig
six times seven is forty-two

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gehalt, deverbal from gehalten (“to keep still, retain, preserve, imprison”), itself from halten (“to hold”). The earliest attested sense of the noun is “custody, prison”. In some southern dialects it also means “room, container, closet”. The modern sense develops in the 15th century, at first in the context of coins and metal alloys.

vocabList.definition: chocolate bar, bar of chocolate, candy bar
vocabList.etym: From Schokolade +‎ -n- +‎ Tafel.

vocabList.definition: to donate, to give as charity
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German spenden, from Old High German spentōn (“to consume, use, spend”), from Proto-West Germanic *spendōn (“to spend”), from Latin expendō.
vocabList.usage:
Blut spenden.
to donate blood.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German mūl, mūle (“snout, mouth”), from Old High German *mūl, mūla (“snout”), from Proto-Germanic *mūlą, *mūlō (“muzzle, snout”), from Proto-Indo-European *mū- (“lips, muzzle”).
From the accusative of Middle High German wīle (modern Weile), from Old High German wīla, from Proto-West Germanic *hwīlu, from Proto-Germanic *hwīlō.
vocabList.usage:
Ich kann nicht kommen, weil ich krank bin.
I can't come because I'm sick.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German dienst, dienest, from Old High German dionest, dionōst, from Proto-Germanic *þewanōstaz. Compare the Old English þēonest, þēnest. See also German dienen.
From Middle High German dort, from Old High German doret.
From Middle High German hingān, from Old High German hinagān. Equivalent to hin- +‎ gehen.
vocabList.usage:
Du musst woanders hingehen, um das zu finden.
You'll have to go elsewhere to find that.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German lëben and Old High German lebēn, from Proto-West Germanic *libbjan, from Proto-Germanic *libjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *leyp- (“leave, cling, linger”).
From Middle High German snīen, from Old High German snīwan, from Proto-West Germanic *snīwan, from Proto-Germanic *snīwaną.
Since the 15th century, ein- +‎ richten.
From Middle High German geschenke, equivalent to ge- +‎ schenken.
From Middle High German siher, from Old High German sihur, from Proto-West Germanic *sikur (“secure, sure”), from Latin sēcūrus (“worryless; carefree; secure”).

From the same root as Gewicht (“weight”) + -ig (“-y”), thus pertaining to wiegen (“to weigh”). See also gewichtig, a (formal or elevated) synonym of wichtig. Weight is often used as a metaphor for importance;
compare German schwerwiegend (“serious, grave”), as well as English weighty, heavy.
vocabList.usage:
Dieser Punkt war ihm sehr wichtig.
That point was very important to him. / He considered that point very important.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ruofen, from Old High German ruofan, hruofan, from Proto-West Germanic *hrōpan, from Proto-Germanic *hrōpaną. Cognate with Dutch roepen, English roop, which see. Alongside there existed a weak Middle High German ruofen, from Old High German (h)ruofen. Weak conjugation is attestable until the 19th century. It indirectly lingers in the umlautless present forms, as against obsolete du rüfst, er rüft. (Lack of umlaut on rounded diphthong before labial is regular in Upper German, but it has only established itself here, not in laufen and saufen.)
vocabList.usage: um Hilfe rufen ― to cry for help

vocabList.definition:
: to put, place, positionsuch that it stands upright

 to pose, to lodge

to provide, to afford, to place at someone's disposal

to encounter and stop

to set, adjust,first-person singular present
drum set, drum kit, drums, percussion
vocabList.etym: Ca. 1900, from schlagen (“to beat”) +‎ Zeug (“equipment”).
From Middle High German fertec, from Old High German fartīg, from the noun fart (“journey”). Cognate with Dutch vaardig, Low German fardig, Old English fierd (“expedition, campaign”).
From Middle High German jeman, ieman, iemant, from Old High German ioman, eoman, equivalent to je +‎ man.

From Middle High German nihtes niht (“nothing of nothing”), a reenforcing construction with niht. Compare French rien de rien, Spanish nada de nada. See nicht.[1] Cognate with Dutch niets, Low German nix, Hunsrik nichs.
vocabList.usage:
Ich weiß, dass ich nichts weiß.
I know that I know nothing.

vocabList.etym: Deverbal from quatschen.
From Middle High German obe, ob, from Proto-Germanic *jabai (“when, if”). Compare English if.
vocabList.usage:
Ich weiß nicht, ob sie krank ist.
I don't know if she's sick

vocabList.etym: Formally from Middle High German lieben, alteration (based on liep) of rarer liuben (“to make or be dear, to treat in a friendly way”), from Old High German liuben, equivalent to lieb +‎ -en.
From Middle High German ërnst, from Old High German ernust, from Proto-West Germanic *ernust, from Proto-Germanic *ernustuz, whence also English earnest.
Inherited from Middle High German and Old High German glat, from Proto-West Germanic *glad.

From Middle High German hovelich (“in accordance with the customs of the court”), which is derived from Middle High German hof, from Old High German hof, from Proto-West Germanic *hof, from Proto-Germanic *hufą.[1] By surface analysis, Hof +‎ lich. In a similar way is Old French cortois derived from cort.
From early modern Dutch gardine (contemporary Dutch gordijn), from French courtine, from Old French cortine, from Late Latin cōrtīna (“curtain”).
Kleider (“clothes”) +‎ Schrank (“cabinet”)
stereo- +‎ Anlage
Compound of an- (“on, at”) +‎ ziehen (“pull”).
vocabList.usage:
Sie zieht sich sehr elegant an.
She dresses very elegantly.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German sloȥ, from Old High German sloȥ, ablaut to the verb schließen. Cognate with Dutch slot (“lock”), Hunsrik Schloss (“lock”), English slot.

From Middle High German swāger, from Old High German swāger, swāgur, from Proto-West Germanic *swāgr, from Proto-Germanic *swēgraz (“husband's brother”), from Proto-Indo-European *swēḱurós (“brother-in-law”), derived from Proto-Indo-European *swéḱuros (“husband's father”).
vocabList.usage:
Ist dieser Schwager der Mann Ihrer Schwester oder der Bruder Ihrer Frau?
Is this brother-in-law your sister’s husband or your wife’s brother?

vocabList.etym: From Einkauf (“purchase”) +‎ -s- +‎ Zentrum (“center”).
From kneipen, an archaic variant of kneifen (“to pinch, squeeze”).

From Middle High German vere, from Old High German *fera, from Proto-Germanic *farjǭ (“ferry”), derived from *farjaną (“to bring, carry”), the causative form of *faraną (“to travel”), whence German fahren. Akin to Dutch veer, English ferry, Danish færge and Swedish färja.
an- +‎ halten (“to stop”)
From Middle High German ban, from Old High German *bana, from Proto-West Germanic *banu, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *banō. Cognate with Luxembourgish Bunn, Dutch baan.
vocabList.usage:
Sie bricht sich ihre eigene Bahn.
She blazes her own trail.

vocabList.etym: Bahn +‎ Hof
From Middle High German bevinden, from Old High German bifindan, from Proto-West Germanic *bifinþan. Equivalent to be- +‎ finden.
vocabList.usage:
Der Tresor befindet sich hinter dem Bild im Wohnzimmer.
The safe is situated behind the picture in the living room.

vocabList.etym: Sicherheit +‎ Gurt
Kegel +‎ -en
Sport +‎ Platz
From Middle High German erbrechen, from Old High German irbrehhan. Equivalent to er- +‎ brechen
vocabList.usage:
Er erbricht sich.
He is vomiting.

vocabList.etym: über- +‎ geben. Cognate with English overgive.

From Middle High German leffel, from Old High German leffil, attested as earlier ᛚᚨᛈᛖᛚᚨ (lapela), from Proto-West Germanic *lapil, from Proto-Germanic *lapilaz (“spoon”), ultimately derived from *lap- (“to lick; to lap”). See English lap. Cognates include Dutch lepel, [1] Yiddish לעפֿל (lefl).

16th century, from Middle French ananas and/or Dutch ananas, themselves from Portuguese ananás, from Old Tupi naná.
In sense two, an abbreviation of Ananaserdbeere (literally “pineapple strawberry”), translating French fraise ananas.
Kartoffel (“potato”) +‎ Brei (“mash”)
From Middle High German obez, from Old High German obaz, from Proto-West Germanic *obaet.
Borrowed from French sauce, from Old French sauce, sause, sausse, salse, from Latin salsa.
16th century, from Latin portio.
From Middle High German bluome, from Old High German bluomo, from Proto-West Germanic *blōmō (“flower”).
vocabList.usage:
Insekten helfen Blumen bei der Reproduktion.
Insects help flowers reproduce.

vocabList.etym: Plural of Nachricht (“message”)
Inherited from Middle High German uzvluc, uȥvluc.[1][2] By surface analysis, deverbal from ausfliegen.
From Middle High German entkomen; ent- +‎ kommen.
vocabList.usage:
Der Fuchs ist der Falle entkommen.
The fox escaped the trap.

vocabList.etym: nach- +‎ Teil, formed as an antonym of Vorteil (“advantage”).
From Middle High German rouch, from Old High German rouh, from Proto-West Germanic *rauki, from Proto-Germanic *raukiz.

From Middle High German schor(n)stein, Old High German scorrenstein. The first element is from schore (“support”), related to the root of scheren (“to cut”); the second element is from Stein (“stone”).[1]
From um- +‎ Welt. In the biological sense first used by Jakob Johann von Uexküll (1909).
From Middle High German vlëc, from Old High German flec, flek, from Proto-West Germanic *flekkō, from Proto-Germanic *flekka- (“spot, mark”). Cognate with Dutch vlek, English fleck.
From Kraft (“power”) +‎ Werk (“factory”). Cognate with Danish kraftværk, Norwegian and Swedish kraftverk.
From the verb zeugen. Cognate with Dutch getuige.
From Middle High German [Term?], from Old High German sīta, from Proto-Germanic *sīdǭ. Cognate with Dutch zijde, Low German Siede, English side, Swedish sida.

From Wort (“word”) +‎ -er- +‎ Buch (“book”). Cognate with English wordbook, Dutch woordenboek, West Frisian wurdboek, Danish ordbog, Faroese orðabók, Icelandic orðabók, Norwegian Bokmål ordbok, Norwegian Nynorsk ordbok, Swedish ordbok and Volapük vödabuk.
From heraus- +‎ finden. Compare English find out.
From Middle High German loben, from Old High German lobēn or lobōn.
From Middle High German ūzbilden. Equivalent to aus- +‎ bilden.

vocabList.definition: a wall, usually one made of stone or concrete
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German mūre, from Old High German mūra, from Proto-West Germanic *mūrā, from Latin mūrus, from Proto-Italic *moiros, from Proto-Indo-European *mey-. Cognate with Yiddish מויער (moyer).
From Middle High German lancsam, from Old High German lancsam, from Proto-West Germanic *langasam (“lengthy, long-lasting”), equivalent to lang +‎ -sam.
Borrowed from French niveau. Doublet of Level and Libelle.
From Middle High German bër m, Old High German bero m, from Proto-West Germanic *berō, from Proto-Germanic *berô, conventionally taken to be a taboo-avoidance term derived from the word for "brown".
um- +‎ Laut
Inherited from Middle French pain, from Old French pain, from Latin pānem.
First attested in the 17th century. From ober- (“upper”) +‎ Fläche (“flat area, surface”), a calque of Latin superficiēs.
From Benutzer +‎ Oberfläche.
aktualisieren (weak, third-person singular present aktualisiert, past tense aktualisierte, past participle aktualisiert, auxiliary haben)
be- +‎ arbeiten
vocabList.usage:
Jeder darf die Artikel bearbeiten.
Anyone can edit the articles.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German doch, from Old High German doh, from Proto-West Germanic *þauh, from Proto-Germanic *þauh. Cognate to Old English þēah (English though).
From Middle High German durch, from Old High German duruh, from Proto-Germanic *þurhw. Cognate with English through, thorough, Dutch door, West Frisian troch, Yiddish דורך (durkh).
vocabList.usage:
Das Haus wurde durch ein Feuer zerstört.
The house was destroyed by fire.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gemein, from Old High German gimeini, from Proto-West Germanic *gamainī. Cognate with Old English gemǣne, English mean, Dutch gemeen, Danish gemen, Swedish gemen and Norwegian gemen.[1]

vocabList.definition:
to follow  From Middle High German volgen, from Old High German folgēn, from Proto-West Germanic *folgēn, from Proto-Germanic *fulgāną. Doublet of  followen.
,third-person singular present

vocabList.etym: ganz +‎ Tag +‎ -ig
From Middle High German beheben (“to take away”), equivalent to be- +‎ heben.
From Regen +‎ Rinne.

vocabList.definition: a form of slight or beginning male pattern baldness where the hairline has receded on the temples and the sides of the forehead, but less so in the middle
vocabList.etym: From Geheimrat (“privy councillor”) +‎ -s- +‎ Ecken (“corners”).
From Middle High German [Term?], from Old High German pflanza, borrowed from Latin planta. Cognate with Hunsrik and Luxembourgish Planz. Doublet of Clan.
vocabList.usage:
Der Garten war voll mit vielen verschiedenen Arten von Pflanzen.
The garden was full of many different kinds of plants.

vocabList.etym: From late Middle High German nuor, contracted from older niwer, newære, from Old High German niwāri, ni wāri (“were it not”). Cognate with Yiddish נאָר (nor), Dutch maar, Old English nǣre.
vocabList.usage:
Nur reife Kirschen dürfen auf den Kuchen.
Only ripe cherries may go on the cake.

vocabList.etym: From ent- +‎ werfen. Compare Dutch ontwerpen.
Equivalent to nach dem, an inflected form which has been used together as a conjunction from Old High German nâh diu.
Inherited from Middle High German spil(e)n, from Old High German spilōn, from Proto-West Germanic *spilōn.
vocabList.usage:
Die Kinder spielen draußen.
The children are playing outside.

vocabList.etym: From manch +‎ Mal.

From Middle High German iemer (also imer, immer), from Old High German iomēr (“always”). From io (“always”) +‎ mēr (“more”). Cognate with Dutch immer, German Low German immer, ümmer, jümmer, jümmers, Middle English a mare, aa mare (“evermore”).
vocabList.usage:
Irgendwo scheint immer die Sonne.
The sun is always shining somewhere.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ëzzen, from Old High German ezzan, akin to Old Saxon etan, compare Dutch eten.
vocabList.usage:
Das Trinken lernt der Mensch schon früh, und später erst das Essen.
So soll der Mensch aus Dankbarkeit das Trinken nicht vergessen.
Man learns to drink early on, and only later to eat.
So man will not, out of gratitude, forget to drink.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German kochen, from Old High German kohhōn, from Proto-West Germanic *kokōn (“to cook”).
From Middle High German kleidunge, from kleiden (“to clothe”), from Kleid, from Old High German *kleid, from Proto-Germanic *klaiþą (“cloth”). Cognate with Dutch kleding, English clothing.
From Middle High German sëhen, from Old High German sëhan, from Proto-West Germanic *sehwan.
From Middle High German schuo, levelled variant of schuoch (inflected schuo(h)-), from Old High German scuoh (“shoe”), from Proto-West Germanic *skōh. More at shoe.
From Middle High German vile, from Old High German filu (“many”), from Proto-West Germanic *felu, from Proto-Germanic *felu, from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₁-. More at fele.
vocabList.usage:
Es ist viel passiert.
Much has happened.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German lernen, from Old High German lernēn, lirnēn, from Proto-West Germanic *liʀnēn. Cognate with Old English leornian (Modern English learn). Related to lehren.
From Middle High German vrosch, from Old High German frosk (“frog”), from Proto-West Germanic *frosk (“frog”), from Proto-Germanic *fruskaz (“frog”), from Proto-Indo-European *prew- (“jump, hop”).
fahren (“drive/ride”) +‎ Rad (“wheel”). Compare Dutch rijwiel.
From an (“on”) +‎ Statt (“stead”). Compare English instead.
vocabList.usage:
Anstatt mich anzurufen, ging er mit seinen Freunden ins Kino.
Instead of calling me, he went to the movies with his friends.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German maht, from Old High German maht. Cognate with Dutch macht, English might.
vocabList.usage:
Die Kanzlerin übernahm die Macht im Jahr 2005.
The Chancellor took power in 2005.

vocabList.definition: to make, to produce, to create
vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German machen, from Old High German mahhōn, from Proto-West Germanic *makōn, from Proto-Indo-European *mag- (“to knead, mix, make”). Cognate with Dutch maken, Low German maken, English make.

From Middle High German noch, nog, from Old High German noh, from Proto-West Germanic *noh, from Proto-Germanic *nuh, from Proto-Indo-European *nu (“now”) + *-kʷe (“and, also”). Cognate to Dutch nog and noch (which are etymologically the same word).
From Middle High German ieweder, from Old High German ioweder, from io + wedar. Compare English either, Dutch ieder.
Borrowed from French passer. Compare English pass.
vocabList.usage:
Wie konnte das nur passieren?
How could that have happened?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German dāheim, dāheime, darheime, from Old High German dārheime (“at home”), equivalent to da +‎ heim. Compare Middle High German heime (“home, at home”, adverb), Old High German heime, heimi (“home, at home”, adverb).

From Middle High German warumme, war umme, warumbe, war umbe, from Old High German wār umbe. Equivalent to wo (“where”) +‎ um (“in order to, for the purpose of”), thus “for what purpose”. Doublet of worum, but with the older vocalism preserved. Compare Dutch waarom, which has both meanings.

From Middle High German leiten, from Old High German leiten, from Proto-West Germanic *laidijan, akin to Old English lǣdan (English lead), Old Saxon lēdian, Old Norse leiða. Cognate with English lead.
From Middle High German halten, from Old High German haltan, from Proto-West Germanic *haldan, from Proto-Germanic *haldaną.
15th century, equivalent to regieren (“to reign”) +‎ -ung.

vocabList.definition: to, towards,Contraction of zu der (“to the (feminine)”).
vocabList.etym: A contraction of zu + der. Compare Dutch ter.
Inherited from Middle High German eigenlīche, equivalent to eigen +‎ -lich. Compare Dutch eigenlijk.
vocabList.usage:
Das wird zwar oft behauptet, aber das stimmt eigentlich gar nicht.
People often claim that, but that's actually wrong.

vocabList.etym: By surface analysis, an +‎ fechten.
vocabList.usage:
Hunderte Händler des unter Gläubigerschutz arbeitenden US-Autobauers Chrysler wollen ihre Vertragsauflösung anfechten.
Hundreds of trade companions of the US car manufacturer Chrysler which is under bankruptcy protection, want to contest the dissolvement of their contract.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ērest, from Old High German ērist, from Proto-West Germanic *airist.
From Middle High German [Term?]. Deverbal from berufen (literally “calling”).

Shortened from Middle High German enwec, from Old High German in weg, corresponding to modern in +‎ Weg. The first syllable is still seen in dialectal forms with e-; compare Luxembourgish ewech. Cognate with Dutch weg, Hunsrik wech, English away.
From Middle High German wër, from Old High German wër, from Proto-West Germanic *hwaʀ. Related to wo.
From Middle High German sich, from Old High German sih, from Proto-Germanic *sek. Compare Yiddish זיך (zikh), Dutch zich. Unrelated to sicher.

From Middle High German hiute, from Old High German hiutu, a contraction of earlier *hiu tagu, from Proto-West Germanic *hiu dagu, from Proto-Germanic *hinō dagō (“on this day”, from *hiz + *dagaz). Cognate with Old English hēodæġ (“today”) and Dutch heden (“today”).
Compare German heuer from hiu (“in this”) +‎ jāru (“year”).
vocabList.usage:
Heute ist Montag
Today is monday

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German tisch, from Old High German tisc, from Proto-West Germanic *disk (“dish”).
vocabList.usage:
Kommt, der Tisch ist gedeckt!
Come, the table is set!

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German durst, from Old High German durst, thurst, from Proto-West Germanic *þurstu, from Proto-Germanic *þurstuz, from Proto-Indo-European *ters- (“dry”).
Inherited from Middle High German gelīch, from Old High German gilīh, from Proto-West Germanic *galīk, from Proto-Germanic *galīkaz, from *ga- + *-līkaz.
vocabList.usage:
Zwei plus zwei ist gleich vier.
Two plus two is equal to four.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German and Old High German māl, from Proto-West Germanic *māl, from Proto-Germanic *mēlą. See also Mahl (“meal”), which is ultimately the same word. Cognate with English meal.

vocabList.definition: to ask, to beg, to plead, to request ,third-person singular present

vocabList.etym: A contraction of in + das.
vocabList.usage:
Ich bin ins Kino gegangen.
I went to the cinema.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German [Term?], from Old High German offanlīh (“open, public”) and offanlīhho (“openly, publicly”). Equivalent to offen +‎ -lich.

From Middle High German bewegen, from Old High German biwegan, from Proto-West Germanic *biwegan, derived from Proto-Germanic *weganą (“to move”),[1] which stems from Proto-Indo-European *weǵʰ-. Compare English beweigh.

vocabList.definition:
will, to be going to,  From Middle High German wërden, from Old High German werdan, from Proto-West Germanic *werþan, from Proto-Germanic *werþaną. Cognate with Dutch worden, obsolete English worth, Swedish varda, Norwegian Nynorsk verta, and also with Latin vertō (“to turn”).
,third-person singular present of werden
vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle Scots word, from Middle English word, from Old English word (“word”), from Proto-Germanic *wurdą (“word”), from Proto-Indo-European *werdʰh₁om (“word”).
From Middle High German gesuntheit. By surface analysis, gesund (“healthy”) +‎ -heit (“-ness, -hood”). Compare Dutch gezondheid.

vocabList.definition: to imply, to mean, to signify, to indicate, to spell, to betoken
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German bediuten, betiuten, from Old High German bidiuten. Equivalent to be- +‎ deuten.
From Middle High German heiȥen, from Old High German heiȥan, from Proto-West Germanic *haitan, from Proto-Germanic *haitaną.
vocabList.usage:
Ich werde Lutz genannt, aber ich heiße Ludger.
They call me Lutz, but my name is Ludger.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German nëmen, from Old High German nëman, from Proto-West Germanic *neman, from Proto-Germanic *nemaną, from Proto-Indo-European *nem- (“to give or take ones due”).
vocabList.usage:
Wer hat meinen Hut genommen?
Who took my hat?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German klingen, Old High German klingan, from Proto-West Germanic *klingan, from Proto-Germanic *klinganą. More at clink.

vocabList.definition:
to understand
to hear and interpret

to comprehend, make sense of

to take, to see, to gather 

to know, have knowledge or understanding of
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German verstān, virstēn, vorstēn, ferstān, from Old High German firstān, firstēn, from Proto-Germanic *frastāną, equivalent to ver- +‎ stehen. Cognate with Bavarian versteh, Dutch verstaan, Middle Low German vorstān. Compare also English forstand.
vocabList.usage:
Ich verstehe dich nicht bei dem Lärm.
I can't understand you with this noise.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German daȥ, from Old High German daȥ, from Proto-Germanic *þat. Compare Dutch dat, Low German dat, datt, English that. Doublet of das. Distinction from das is purely orthographical convention.
vocabList.usage:
Ich habe gehört, dass du krank bist.
I was told that you are sick.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German ander, from Old High German andar, from Proto-West Germanic *anþar.
From Middle High German saz, satz, deverbal from setzen. Compare Yiddish זעץ (zets, “a punch”).
vocabList.usage:
Dieser Satz scheint mir grammatikalisch falsch zu sein.
This sentence seems grammatically wrong to me.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German weln, from welen, wellen, from Old High German wellen, from Proto-West Germanic *walljan, from Proto-Germanic *waljaną, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *welh₁-.
vocabList.usage:
Ich wähle diese Hose da, die mit der Bügelfalte.
I'm choosing these pants here, the ones with the crease.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German müeȥen, from Old High German muoȥan, from Proto-West Germanic *mōtan.

From Middle High German wërden, from Old High German werdan, from Proto-West Germanic *werþan, from Proto-Germanic *werþaną. Cognate with Dutch worden, obsolete English worth, Swedish varda, Norwegian Nynorsk verta, and also with Latin vertō (“to turn”).
vocabList.usage:
Ich werde nach Hause gehen.
I will go home.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German sagen, from Old High German sagēn, from Proto-West Germanic *saggjan, from Proto-Germanic *sagjaną, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *sekʷ-.

From Middle High German kennen, from Old High German kennen, from Proto-West Germanic *kannijan (“to know”), from Proto-Germanic *kannijaną (“to know”), a causative form of *kunnaną formed with the suffix *-janą. Cognate to Bavarian kennan, Dutch and Low German kennen, Scots and English ken (“to know”).
From Middle High German wort. Compare Dutch woord, English word, Danish ord. Doublet of Verb.
vocabList.usage:
Im Deutschen gibt es wenig Wörter, die mit y geschrieben werden.
In German there are few words spelt with y.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German liute, from Old High German liuti, also liudi, from Proto-West Germanic *liud(i), from Proto-Germanic *liudīz (“people”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁lewdʰ- (“man, people”).
Adverbialized noun Bisschen, from Bissen (“a bit, bite”) +‎ -chen (“diminutive”)

vocabList.definition: to gladden, to make glad, to make pleased
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German vrö(u)wen, vre(u)wen, from Old High German frewen, frouwen, a derivation of Old High German frō, frao (“glad”). Equivalent to froh (“glad”) +‎ -en. Compare English frolic.
vocabList.usage:
[Es] freut mich, Sie kennenzulernen.
I'm pleased to meet you. ([It] pleases me to get to know you. (formal))

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German anwalde, from Old High German anawalto, from Old English anweald.

From Middle High German ūf, from Old High German ūf, from Proto-Germanic *upp. This form with a lengthened vowel is originally Upper German. Central German forms were Middle High German uf and (western) up. Compare Dutch op, Low German op, Luxembourgish op, English up.

From Middle High German nāh, from Old High German nāh with preservation of word-final -h as -ch; thus pertaining to modern nah (“near”) (from Old High German inflected nāh-), from Proto-West Germanic *nāhw, from Proto-Germanic *nēhw. Cognate with Dutch na, English nigh.
From lang (“long”, adjective) +‎ Weile (“while”, noun). Cognate with Hunsrik langweilich.

vocabList.definition: people , folk, peeps , guys,Alternative form of Leute
vocabList.etym: Leut pl
From Latin concurrentia (“concurrence; competition”). Compare English concurrence.
From Middle High German wār, wǣre, from Old High German wār, wāri, from Proto-West Germanic *wār, from Proto-Germanic *wēraz.

From Middle High German drucken, from Old High German drucchen, drukken, from Proto-West Germanic *þrukkijan (“to press”). Doublet of drücken (“to press, push”) with Upper German lack of umlaut before a velar geminate; the first German printers were in the south. Established as technical term for printing in the 17th century (see also bedrucken).
From Middle High German āne (“without”), from Old High German āna, ānu, āno (“without”), from Proto-Germanic *ēnu, *ēnō (“without”).
vocabList.usage:
Ich habe viele Jahre vergeudet, ohne dir zu sagen, was du mir bedeutest.
I wasted many years without telling you what you mean to me.

vocabList.etym: einrichten +‎ -ung
mögen +‎ -lich; cognate with Hunsrik meeghlich, Dutch mogelijk.
vocabList.usage:
Es ist möglich, ungesund zu essen und trotzdem gesund zu bleiben.
It is possible to eat unhealthily and stay healthy nonetheless.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German richtunge, from Old High German rihtunga, from Proto-West Germanic *rihtungu. By surface analysis, richten +‎ -ung.
Standard +‎ mäßig

vocabList.definition: willingly,Alternative form of gern. (Both are roughly equally frequent.)
vocabList.etym: From Old Dutch *gerno, from Proto-West Germanic *gernō, from Proto-Germanic *gernô.

vocabList.definition: to go, to walk,singular imperative of gehen
to live, reside, dwell,second-person singular present of wohnen

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German echt, borrowed from Middle Low German echt (“lawful, genuine”). The original form is Middle Low German ēhaft (“lawful”), from ē (“law”) (related to modern Ehe); then ēhacht by the Low German development -ft- → -cht- (compare Nichte); and eventually contracted into echt. Cognate to Old High German ēhaft (“honourable”) and Dutch echt.
vocabList.usage:
Die Jacke ist aus echtem Leder.
The jacket is made of genuine leather.

vocabList.definition: terrific, superb, etc.,Switzerland and Liechtenstein standard spelling of großartig

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German dann, from Old High German danne, from Proto-West Germanic *þan. Cognate with English then.
vocabList.usage:
Ich ziehe mich erst an, dann frühstücke ich.
First I'm getting dressed, then I'll have breakfast.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wie, a merger of two interrelated forms: 1.) Old High German hwio, from older hwēo, from Proto-Germanic *hwaiwa; cognate with Gothic 𐍈𐌰𐌹𐍅𐌰 (ƕaiwa). 2.) Old High German hwē, hwie, from Proto-Germanic *hwē; cognate with Gothic 𐍈𐌴 (ƕē). The latter is a variant of Proto-Germanic *hwī, whence English why, and is further a fossilized instrumental case of *hwaz, *hwat (“who, what”). Form 1 is also related to this stem. Outside of High German the only direct modern cognate is Limburgish wie.
vocabList.usage:
Wie groß bist du?
How tall are you?

vocabList.definition: much, a lot,strong/mixed nominative/accusative feminine singular
vocabList.etym: Corresponds to Old Occitan viola (cf. modern Occitan viula). Possibly from Medieval Latin vitula.

From Middle High German zaln, zalen, from Old High German zalōn, from Proto-West Germanic *talōn, from Proto-Germanic *talōną (“to tell, recount; to count, reckon”). Cognate with Bavarian zoin, English tale, Dutch talen, Swedish tala, Danish tal. Equivalent to Zahl +‎ -en.
vocabList.usage:
Ich muss meine Steuern zahlen.
I have to pay my taxes.

vocabList.definition:
to be,first-person plural present of sein
Wir sind hier drüben. ― We are over here.
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German sint. See sein for more. The modern spelling with d probably because nd is much more frequent in German than nt; perhaps also influenced by the present participle in -end.
From einladen +‎ -ung.
From Middle High German geburttac, from Old High German giburtitag, from Proto-West Germanic *gaburdidag; equivalent to Geburt (“birth”) +‎ -s- +‎ Tag (“day”).
From Middle High German gerat, from Old High German girat, equivalent to ge- + the root of Rad (“wheel”).
vocabList.usage:
Zahlen, die durch zwei teilbar sind, heißen gerade Zahlen.
Numbers divisible by two are called even numbers.

vocabList.etym: Cognate with Low German weer.

From Middle High German kurz, from Old High German kurz, from Proto-West Germanic *kurt, from Latin curtus. Compare also native Old High German *skurz, scurz and Middle High German schurz. Cognate with Dutch and Low German kort, English curt, Swedish kort.

From Middle High German lücke, lucke, from Old High German luccha, probably originally referring to a closable opening. Doublet of Loch (“hole”) and Luke (“hatch”), and see the former for more.[1] Related to English lacuna.

vocabList.definition: you, thou,(personal) dative of du; you, to you.
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German dir, from Old High German dir, from Proto-West Germanic *þiʀ, from Proto-Germanic *þiz.
From Buchstabe (“letter”) +‎ -ieren (“-ise, -ify”).

vocabList.definition: word as an isolated unit|gender:neuter,nominative plural of Wort

vocabList.etym: Reihe +‎ Folge
From Deutsch +‎ Kurs.

17th century, from French être capot (“not having won any trick in a card game”, as in German schwarz sein). The further origin is uncertain, though it probably stems from a figurative usage of capot (“hood”); Pfeiffer suggests an image of "a hood pulled over one's head and face" > "restrained and unable to perform actions" (DWDS). Compare Dutch kapot.

vocabList.definition: to address informally using the pronoun du, to thou
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German duzen, dutzen, dützen, from Old High German *dūzzen, *dūezzen, equivalent to du +‎ -zen. Compare Middle English thouten.

From Middle High German weinec, wēnec (“marginal”), from Old High German *weinag, wēnag (“miserable”), from Proto-Germanic *wainagaz. The form with -ei- is original; that with -ē- arose through conflation with the morphologically simpler Old High German wē (“woe”), akin to English woe. The diphthong -ei- later on regularly became -ē- in several dialects, which further strengthened the monophthongal form wenig. Cognate with Dutch weinig, Low German weinig, Hunsrik wenich, Yiddish ווייניק (veynik).
From bestellen +‎ -ung.

From Middle High German gërne, from Old High German gërno, from Proto-West Germanic *gernō, from Proto-Germanic *gernô (“willingly, gladly”), an adverbial form of *gernaz (“eager, willing”). Akin to German Low German geren (Paderbornisch), Dutch gaarne, English yern, Swedish gärna, Danish gerne.
vocabList.usage:
Markus fährt gern Fahrrad.
Markus enjoys biking.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German bestellen, from Old High German bistellen. Equivalent to be- +‎ stellen.

From Middle High German sunst, sust, sus, from Old High German sus (“thus”), from Proto-West Germanic *sus, from *swā (“so”), formally related to Proto-West Germanic *þus (“thus”). Cognate with Hunsrik sunst, Old Saxon sus (Middle Low German süs),[1] archaic Dutch zonst (“otherwise”), Alemannic German sus and suscht.
vocabList.usage:
Beeil dich, sonst kommen wir zu spät.
Hurry up, otherwise we'll be late.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German etewaʒ, from Old High German eddeshwaz, from edde- +‎ hwaz. The first element is of obscure origin, but possibly related to Proto-Germanic *ehþau (“otherwise, or, but if”), source of modern oder (“or”).

vocabList.definition: to be right, to be correct, to be proper, to be true,third-person singular present of stimmen

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German zesamene, zesamne, zesamen (“together”), from Old High German zisamane (“together”). From zu- (“to”) +‎ sammen (“together”) (in Modern German, sammen is only found in compounds), from Proto-West Germanic *saman, from Proto-Germanic *samanai (“together”), from Proto-Indo-European *sem- (“together, one”). Cognate with Middle English to-samen (“together”). Related to obsolete English sam (“together”), whose earlier form was samen.
From Proto-Samic *lësē.
From Middle High German gel (inflected gelwe), from Old High German gelo, from Proto-West Germanic *gelu, from Proto-Germanic *gelwaz.
From Middle High German laden, lade (“board; plank; shutter; shop”), from Old High German *lado, from Proto-Germanic *laþô. Probably akin to German Latte, English lath. Unrelated to Lade.
vocabList.usage:
Wann schließen hier die Läden?
When do the shops close around here?

vocabList.etym: From wirk(en) +‎ -lich. Cognate with Bavarian wirkli, wirkle, Hunsrik werklich and Dutch werkelijk.
From Middle High German alles, from Old High German also, alsō (“as, like”); equivalent to all + so. Cognate with English also, as.
vocabList.usage:
Er aß zu viel Kuchen, also wurde er krank.
He ate too much cake, so he got sick.

vocabList.definition: on it, on that,Alternative form of daran
vocabList.etym: Short form of daran
See the corresponding lemma form.

vocabList.definition: will,first/third-person singular subjunctive II of werden

vocabList.etym: be- +‎ Sieg (“victory”) +‎ -en
As a feminine, apocope of Frühe. As a neuter, nominalization of früh.
From Middle High German üeben, uoben, from Old High German uoben, from Proto-Germanic *ōbijaną (“to do, practice”).
vocabList.usage:
Meine Tochter übt Klavier.
My daughter is practicing piano.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German venster, from Old High German fenstar, from Proto-West Germanic *fenestr (“window”).
vocabList.usage: sich weit aus dem Fenster lehnen ― to go out on a limb

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German hel (“resounding, loud, shining, bright”), from Old High German hel (“resounding”), from Proto-Germanic *halliz (“resounding”), from Proto-Germanic *hellaną (“to resound, make a sound”), from Proto-Indo-European *kelh₁- (“to call, make noise”). Cognate with Dutch hel.
From dr- +‎ außen; the first component is from a short form of dar-.
From Middle High German vrāgen, from Old High German frāgēn, frahēn/frāhēn, which is indirectly derived from Proto-West Germanic *frāgēn.[1]
vocabList.usage:
Darf ich dich etwas fragen?
May I ask you something?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German unser, from Old High German unsēr, from Proto-West Germanic *unsar.

From Middle High German genoue, genouwe, geneuwe (“narrow, close, exact”), from ge- + nou(we) (“narrow, close, exact”), from Old High German *hnouw (“narrow, close”), from Proto-Germanic *hnawwaz. Cognate with Middle Low German nouwe, nau (“narrow, brief, exact”), Dutch nauw (“narrow, close”), Old English hnēaw (“niggardly, miserly, stingy”), Old Norse hnøggr (“niggardly, stingy, scant”).
From Middle High German stuol, from Old High German stuol, from Proto-West Germanic *stōl.

From Middle High German want, from Old High German want, from Proto-Germanic *wanduz (“fence, wall”), from Proto-Indo-European *wendʰ- (“to turn; bend; wind; twist; braid; weave”). Cognate with English wand although developing a completely distinct meaning.

vocabList.definition:
cabinet , or :
cupboard 
wardrobe, closet 
bookcase
vocabList.etym: From Late Middle High German schranc, from Old High German scranc, from Proto-West Germanic *skrank, from Proto-Germanic *skrankaz (“grid, barrier”), probably derived from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to bend, turn”).[1] Cognate with German Low German Schrank (“barrier, barricade”).
From Middle High German ecke, from Old High German egga, from Proto-West Germanic *aggju, from Proto-Germanic *agjō. Compare English edge.

From Middle High German küssen, from Old High German kussīn, from Proto-West Germanic *kussīn (“cushion, pillow”). The form Kissen with dialectal unrounding was standardised to avoid homophony with küssen (“to kiss”).
From English chill.
From Middle High German bī, from Old High German bī, from Proto-West Germanic *bī, from Proto-Germanic *bi. More at by.
From Old High German lëder, from Proto-Germanic *leþrą. Cognate with German Leder, Dutch leder, English leather, Icelandic leður.

From Middle High German viur, from Old High German fiur, from Proto-West Germanic *fuir, from Proto-Germanic *fōr, from Proto-Indo-European *péh₂wr̥. Compare Dutch vuur, Low German Füer, West Frisian fjoer, English fire, Danish fyr.
From Middle High German danāch, darnāch, from Old High German daranāh, equivalent to da (“there”) +‎ nach (“after”). Compare Yiddish דערנאָך (dernokh).

From Middle High German lœsunge, lōsunge, from Old High German lōsunga (“redemption, payment, ransom, fraud, deception”), from Proto-West Germanic *lausungu, from Proto-Germanic *lausungō, equivalent to lösen +‎ -ung. Cognate with English leasing, Icelandic lausung. Compare also Dutch oplossing.

vocabList.definition: entire, whole, complete,strong genitive masculine/neuter singular
to cancel, to call off,first/third-person plural present

vocabList.etym: From Arbeit +‎ -s- +‎ Schutz.
From Bau +‎ Arbeiter.
bauen (“build”) +‎ Stelle (“place”)
From Middle High German al-ein. Cognate with Middle English al-one, English alone, Dutch alleen, Low German alleene (Münsterländisch), alläine (Sauerländisch).[1]
vocabList.usage:
Er ist ganz allein.
He is all alone.

vocabList.definition: equal,nominalization of gleich: female equivalent of Gleicher: female equal (female who is equal to another person)
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gelīche, from Old High German gilīkī; equivalent to gleich +‎ -e.
From Middle High German vil līchte (“very easily”), thus: “what could easily happen”. Compare the same in German Low German villicht, Dutch wellicht, Saterland Frisian fielicht.
vocabList.usage:
Vielleicht hat er einen Unfall gehabt.
Maybe he’s had an accident.

vocabList.etym: From da +‎ Mal +‎ -s. Compare Yiddish דעמאָלט (demolt) and דעמאָלטס (demolts).
From Middle High German endelīch (“final”), equivalent to Ende (“end”) +‎ -lich (“-ly”). See English endly.
zu +‎ letzter; cognate with Hunsrik zuletst
vocabList.usage:
Ich war zuerst in Aachen, dann in Düsseldorf und zuletzt in Köln.
I was in Aachen first, then in Düsseldorf, and finally in Cologne.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gewon(e)lich, from Old High German giwonalīh (11th c. as adverb giwonalīhho), from Proto-West Germanic *gawunalīk. Cognate with Dutch gewoonlijk, Old English ġewuneliċ. Equivalent to gewohn +‎ -lich, the former being an obsolete variant of gewohnt. The umlaut in Modern German developed under influence of related gewöhnen (Middle High German gewenen).
nach +‎ her.
See nächster. Compare the Dutch preposition naast (“next to”).
neu +‎ -lich

From Middle High German balde, from Old High German baldo, adverb of bald, pald, from Proto-West Germanic *balþ, from Proto-Germanic *balþaz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel-. Cognate with Dutch boud, English bold.
vocabList.usage:
Bald ist der Urlaub vorbei.
The vacation will soon be over.

vocabList.etym: Schub (“push”) +‎ Lade (“box”), 16th century.
From Middle High German mēre, from Old High German mēro, from Proto-West Germanic *maiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *maizô, from Proto-Indo-European *mē- (“many”). See English more for more.
vocabList.usage:
sich für mehr halten
to think that one is something more

vocabList.etym: Borrowed from Italian soglio.
Inherited from Middle High German lange, an adverb to lanc.
From Middle High German deshalp, from Middle High German des, dez (“from that, therefore, thereon”) + halp (“half”). Cognate to Low German diäßhalw (Paderbornisch).

vocabList.definition:
to propose, to advise in favor of
 to recommend
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German enpfelhen, enphelhen, entfelhen, intfelhen, from Old High German intfelhan, intfelahan, from int- +‎  felhan (“to preserve; entrust; confide in; surrender”), with assimilation before f- (see emp-).
vocabList.usage:
Aufgrund ihrer bisherigen Arbeit empfiehlt sich die Fachkraft für die Beförderung.
In view of their previous work, the specialist merits the promotion.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German varwe, from Old High German farawa, from Proto-West Germanic *faru, from Proto-Germanic *farwō.

vocabList.definition: to go, to walk,past participle of gehen
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gegangen, from Old High German gigangan.

vocabList.definition: to go, to walk,first/third-person singular preterite of gehen
vocabList.etym: ging
From Middle High German sīt, from Old High German sīd, from Proto-Germanic *sīþuz. Akin to Old Saxon sīd, Old English sīþ. Related to Dutch sedert and sinds.

From Middle High German aber, aver, from Old High German aber, ābar, abur, aver, avur, afur, from Proto-Germanic *aferą (“behind”). Compare Bavarian owa (“but”), Luxembourgish awer (“but”), Saterland Frisian oaber (“but”), Middle Low German āver, German Low German aver (“but”).
From Proto-Finnic *alëk. Cognates include Finnish alle and Veps alle.
From Middle High German alles, from Old High German also, alsō (“as, like”); equivalent to all + so. Cognate with English also, as.
vocabList.usage:
Er aß zu viel Kuchen, also wurde er krank.
He ate too much cake, so he got sick.

vocabList.etym: From Old High German andar halb, anderhalb (literally “second half”). Anderthalb is the single surviving relic of an older system to describe fractions, which counted from the higher ordinal number rather than the lower cardinal. Compare Old English ōþer healf, Dutch anderhalf, Danish halvanden. Compare also the use of the word halb in the sense of a half-hour before the following hour, such as halb zwei to mean one thirty. The word anderer has since lost the meaning "second", being used solely as "other" in modern German.
vocabList.usage:
In den vergangenen anderthalb Jahren haben wir also schon einiges erreicht.
In the last year and a half, we have notched up some achievements.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German anevāhen, from Old High German anafāhan, from Proto-West Germanic *anafą̄han. Equivalent to an- +‎ fangen.
vocabList.usage:
Das Konzert fängt gleich an.
The concert is beginning shortly.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German antwürte, from Old High German antwurti, from Proto-Germanic *andawurdiją. The gender change from neuter to feminine is due to semantic association with Frage (“question”). See also antworten. Cognate to Dutch antwoord and Afrikaans antwoord.
From Middle High German antwürten, from Old High German antwurten, from Proto-Germanic *andawurdijaną. By surface analysis, Antwort +‎ -en.
vocabList.usage:
Der König antwortete: „Wenn es einen solchen Menschen gibt, dann muss er verrückt sein.”
The King answered, "If such a man exists, he must be mad."

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German art, from Old High German *art, from Proto-West Germanic *ard, from Proto-Germanic *ardiz.

From Middle High German ouch, from Old High German ouh, from Proto-Germanic *auk. Cognate with Dutch ook (“also”), Low German ook (“also”), West Frisian ek (“also, too”), Luxembourgish och (“also”), Swedish och (“and”), Icelandic og (“and”), Danish og (“and”), and archaic English eke (“also”).

From Middle High German ougenblick (“quick glance”), corresponding to Auge (“eye”) +‎ -n- +‎ Blick (“glance”). Cognate to Yiddish אויגנבליק (oygnblik), Luxembourgish Abléck, Dutch ogenblik, Danish øjeblik, Swedish ögonblick, Norwegian øyeblikk, Icelandic augnablik. Compare English eyeblink or blink of an eye.
vocabList.usage:
Sie können einen Taubenkäfig in einem kurzen Augenblick vor den Augen der Zuschauer verschwinden lassen.
You can make a pigeon cage disappear in front of the audience in the blink of an eye.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ūȥer, from Old High German ūȥar. More at aus. Cf. English outer, Norwegian uten-, ytre.
vocabList.usage:
Alle außer dir sind schon unterwegs.
Everyone except for you is already on their way.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German beginnen, from Old High German biginnan, from Proto-West Germanic *biginnan, from Proto-Germanic *biginnaną. Cognate with Low German beginnen, Dutch beginnen, West Frisian begjinne, and English begin.

From Middle High German begrüezen, from Old High German bigruozen, from Proto-West Germanic *bigrōtijan; equivalent to be- +‎ grüßen. Cognate with German Low German begröten, Dutch begroeten, West Frisian begroetsje, English begreet.
vocabList.usage:
Wir begrüßen euch auf unserer Webseite.
We welcome you to our website.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German behalten, from Old High German bihaltan, from Proto-West Germanic *bihaldan. Equivalent to be- +‎ halten. Cognates include Saterland Frisian behoolde (“to keep”), Dutch behouden (“to keep, restrain, preserve”), English behold, Danish and Norwegian beholde (“to keep”) and Swedish behålla (“to keep”).
behandeln +‎ -ung
From Middle High German beide, bēde, from Old High German beide, bēde, from Proto-Germanic *bai.

From Middle High German bīspil, bīspel, from Old High German bīspel (“proverb", "example”), equivalent to bī- (“by-”) + spel (“talk”), the latter from Proto-Germanic *spellą (“news, message, tale”). Cognate with Old English bīspel (“proverb", "example”), English byspel (“example”). Unrelated to spielen (“to play”).

From Middle High German bekomen, from Old High German biqueman, bikweman, from Proto-West Germanic *bikweman, from Proto-Germanic *bikwemaną, equivalent to be- +‎ kommen. Cognate to Dutch bekomen, English become.
vocabList.usage:
Wenn du Männchen machst, bekommst du von mir ein Leckerli.
If you stand on your hind legs, you'll get a treat from me.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German bemerken, from Old High German bimerken, from Proto-West Germanic *bimarkijan. Equivalent to be- +‎ merken. Cognate with Dutch bemerken, also related to Middle Dutch and Middle High German bemarken, and English bemark.
be- +‎ nutzen

From Middle High German bequæme, bekōme (“suitable”), from Old High German biquāmi, derived from biqueman (whence German bekommen). The word seems originally to have been more common in Central and Low German; therefore possibly reinforced by cognate Middle Low German bequēme. The consonantism -qu-, which generally remained more stable in the north than it did in Upper German, may also point to that. Further cognate with Dutch bekwaam, English queem, queme, Swedish bekväm.
From besonder (“special”, adjective) +‎ -s.
From Middle High German beȥȥer, from Old High German beȥȥiro, from Proto-West Germanic *batiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *batizô.

From Middle High German besprechen, from Old High German besprechan, besprehhan (also bisprechōn, bisprehhōn), from Proto-Germanic *bisprekaną (“to speak about, discuss, blame”), equivalent to be- +‎ sprechen. Cognate with English bespeak, Dutch bespreken, West Frisian besprekke.

The adjective is from Middle High German eben, from Old High German eban, the adverb from ebano; from Proto-West Germanic *ebn, from Proto-Germanic *ebnaz and its adverb equivalent. Cognate with Low German even, Dutch even, effen, English even, Danish jævn.
eben +‎ so. Compare English even so.
17th century, from French égal.
ehemals +‎ -ig

From Middle High German eigen, from Old High German eigan, from Proto-West Germanic *aigan, from Proto-Germanic *aiganaz, the past participle of Proto-Germanic *aiganą. Cognate with Dutch eigen, English own.
From Middle High German īlen, from Old High German īlen, from Proto-West Germanic *īlijan (“to make haste, hasten”).
vocabList.usage: jemandem zu Hilfe eilen ― to rush to someone's aid

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German einander, from Old High German compound of ein (“one”) +‎ andar (“other”, modern German ander). Semantically limited by the ein (“one”) to singular contexts, similar to one another or each other.
vocabList.usage:
Sie unterstützten einander, so gut sie konnten.
They supported each other as much as they could.

vocabList.etym: See the etymology of the corresponding lemma form.
From Middle High German einmāle, equivalent to ein +‎ -mal. Compare Middle Low German ênmâl.
vocabList.usage:
Ich werde das nur einmal sagen.
I'm only going to say it once.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German ende, from Old High German enti, from Proto-West Germanic *andī, from Proto-Germanic *andijaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂entíos.
entschuldig(en) +‎ -ung
Middle High German ein(t)weder, Old High German ein(h)wedar.  By surface analysis, ent- +‎ weder.
From Middle High German erinnern, erinneren, from  er- +‎ innern from Old High German innarōn (“to make someone perceive inwardly”), from innar (“inner”), see the preposition in (“in”).
From Middle High German erkennen, from Old High German irkennen, from Proto-West Germanic *uʀkannijan. Equivalent to er- +‎ kennen.
vocabList.usage:
Ich habe dich mit diesem Hut nicht erkannt.
I didn't recognize you in that hat.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German erzellen, from Old High German irzellen. Equivalent to er- +‎ zählen.
vocabList.usage:
Erzähl mir ein Märchen.
Tell me a fairytale.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German etwā, contraction of etewā (also eteswā), from Old High German edde(s)hwār (“somewhere”). For the first component compare etlich, etwas; the second is wo (“where”). A related formation was Middle High German ete(s)wanne, in which the second component is wann (“when”). It yielded modern etwan, which was displaced by the 19th century.
vocabList.usage:
Das Gebäude ist etwa 30 Meter hoch.
The height of the building is approximately 30 metres.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German etewaʒ, from Old High German eddeshwaz, from edde- +‎ hwaz. The first element is of obscure origin, but possibly related to Proto-Germanic *ehþau (“otherwise, or, but if”), source of modern oder (“or”).

From Middle High German vallen, from Old High German fallan, from Proto-West Germanic *fallan, from Proto-Germanic *fallaną, from Proto-Indo-European *pōl-. Akin to Bavarian foin, Low German fallen, Dutch vallen, English fall, Danish falde, Dutch falla.
vocabList.usage:
Der Regen fiel wie aus Eimern.
It rained cats and dogs. (literally: 'The rain fell as if out of buckets.')

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German valsche, valsch, from Old High German *falski, from Proto-West Germanic *falskī (“false, counterfeit”).
vocabList.usage:
eine falsche Beschuldigung
a false accusation

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German vast, vaste, from Old High German fasto (“solidly, strictly, securely”), from Proto-West Germanic *fastō, from Proto-Germanic *fastuz. Cognate with Middle Low German vaste (whence German Low German fast), English fast (adverb). Compare also German fest, English fast (adjective), Dutch vast.
From fehlen in the sense of “to fail”.
