From Middle High German vinden, from Old High German findan, from Proto-West Germanic *finþan, from Proto-Germanic *finþaną. Cognate with Bavarian findn, Low German finden, Dutch vinden, English find, Danish finde.
vocabList.usage:
Ich habe deine Schlüssel gefunden.
I found your keys.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German volgen, from Old High German folgēn, from Proto-West Germanic *folgēn, from Proto-Germanic *fulgāną. Doublet of followen.
vocabList.usage:
Drei Jahre später folgte eine Fortsetzung des ersten Films.
Three years later a sequel followed the first film.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German vrāge, from Old High German frāga, from Proto-West Germanic *frāgu, from Proto-Germanic *frēgō, from Proto-Indo-European *preḱ-.

vocabList.usage:
Wenn jemand die Regeln bricht, geht das gar nicht.
If someone breaks the rules, that is unacceptable.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German gëben, from Old High German gëban, from Proto-West Germanic *geban, from Proto-Germanic *gebaną, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰebʰ-.
From Middle High German genuoc, from Old High German ginuog, from Proto-West Germanic *ganōg, from Proto-Germanic *ganōgaz.[1]
vocabList.usage:
Wir haben nicht genug Geld.
We don't have enough money.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gelouben, gelöuben, from Old High German gilouben, from Proto-West Germanic *galaubijan, from Proto-Germanic *galaubijaną. The form with -au- is Upper German; it was reinforced by the related noun Glaube against the Central German variant with umlaut. Compare however gläubig and abergläubisch.
Inherited from Middle High German gelīch, from Old High German gilīh, from Proto-West Germanic *galīk, from Proto-Germanic *galīkaz, from *ga- + *-līkaz.
vocabList.usage:
Zwei plus zwei ist gleich vier.
Two plus two is equal to four.

vocabList.etym: Glück +‎ -lich. Cognate to Silesian East Central German glücklich, Low German glücklik (Paderbornisch) and Yiddish גליקלעך (gliklekh).
From Middle High German got, from Old High German got, from Proto-West Germanic *god, from Proto-Germanic *gudą. Compare Dutch god, English god, Danish gud, Gothic 𐌲𐌿𐌸 (guþ).
Borrowed from Latin grātulārī.
From Middle High German grunt, from Old High German grunt, from Proto-West Germanic *grundu, from Proto-Germanic *grunduz, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰr̥mtu-.
Compare German Gruß.
From Middle High German günstic, gunstic, equivalent to Gunst +‎ -ig. Cognate with Middle Low German günstich.
vocabList.usage:
Ich werde sie fragen, aber ich warte auf einen günstigen Moment.
I'll ask her, but I'm waiting for an opportune moment.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German guot, from Old High German guot, from Proto-West Germanic *gōd, from Proto-Germanic *gōdaz, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰedʰ- (“to unite, be associated, suit”).
vocabList.usage:
Wir müssen gut sein, um uns gut zu fühlen.
We must be good to feel good.

vocabList.etym: Short for ich wünsche einen guten Tag! (“I wish [you] a good day!”), hence the accusative form of the adjective. Compare Yiddish אַ גוטן טאָג (a gutn tog).

From Middle High German haben, from Old High German habēn (akin to Old Saxon hebbian, Old Norse hafa (Swedish hava/ha), Old Frisian habba, Gothic 𐌷𐌰𐌱𐌰𐌽 (haban), Old English habban), from Proto-West Germanic *habbjan, from Proto-Germanic *habjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *kap- (“to grasp”). Cognates include Bavarian håbn, Yiddish האָבן (hobn), Dutch hebben, English have, Danish have.
From Middle High German halp, from Old High German halb, from Proto-West Germanic *halb, from Proto-Germanic *halbaz. Compare Dutch half, English half, Danish halv.
vocabList.usage:
Er ist seit einem halben Monat nicht mehr hier gewesen.
He hasn’t been here for half a month.

vocabList.etym: From Middle Low German helfte, derived from half (“half”). The form entered Early Modern German via Central German. Equivalent to halb (“half”) +‎ -te. The alternation -b- ↔ -ft- has not been levelled, probably because the same alternation occurs also—for different reasons—in native High German words (compare schreiben ↔ Schrift). Cognate with Dutch helft.
vocabList.usage:
Jeder von uns kriegt die Hälfte.
Each of us gets half.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German hier, from Old High German hier, from Proto-West Germanic *hēr. Cognate with Dutch hier, English here, Swedish här.

From Middle High German hoffen (12th c.), from northern Old High German *hoffōn, from Proto-West Germanic *hopōn. It is uncertain whether the (unattested but probable) Old High German form was inherited or rather borrowed from Old Dutch hopon with implementation of the High German consonantism (which was then still entirely predictable). In fact, some scholars consider that all continental forms go back to Old English hopian, introduced as a religious term by Anglo-Saxon missionaries. The word was at any rate absent from Upper German, where it only established itself in later Middle High German, gradually displacing the now obsolete gedingen. See English hope for more.
vocabList.usage:
Ich hoffe auf eine vollständige Heilung.
I hope for a complete cure.

vocabList.etym: Borrowed from French idée, from Latin idea (“a (Platonic) idea; archetype”), from Ancient Greek ἰδέα (idéa, “notion, pattern”), from εἴδω (eídō, “I see”).
vocabList.usage:
Hast du eine Idee, wo meine Schlüssel sind?
You have any idea where my keys are?

vocabList.etym: From the verb einbegreifen.
irgend (“any; at all”) +‎ wo (“where”)
From Middle High German ja, from Old High German ja, jā (“yes”), from Proto-Germanic *ja (“yes”). Cognate with Yiddish יאָ (yo).
From Middle High German ie, from Old High German io.
From Middle High German jener, from Old High German jenēr, from Proto-West Germanic *jain, from Proto-Germanic *jainaz. Cognate with English yon.
From Middle High German iez, ieze, iezū, iezō, iezuo, from Old High German iozuo (“straightaway, at once; further”), equivalent to je +‎ zu. Compare English yet, Yiddish יעצט (yetst).

From Middle High German kein, back-formation of original nekein (“not any”), from Old High German nihein, from Proto-West Germanic *nehwain, from Proto-Germanic *nehwainaz (“not any”). Compare Dutch geen, Yiddish קיין (keyn). More at none.
From Middle High German klār, clār, formally from Middle Low German klār or Middle Dutch claer and reinforced by Old French cler, both from Latin clārus (“bright”).[1]
From Middle High German künnen, kunnen, from Old High German kunnan, from Proto-West Germanic *kunnan, from Proto-Germanic *kunnaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃- (“to know”).
vocabList.usage:
Kommst du zur Party?
— Nein, ich kann nicht.
Are you coming to the party?
— No, I can’t.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German lanc, from Old High German lang, from Proto-West Germanic *lang, from Proto-Germanic *langaz.
From Middle High German leider, from Old High German leidir, equivalent to the comparative form of leid.
From Middle High German līhen, from Old High German līhan, from Proto-West Germanic *līhwan.
From Middle High German, from Old High German; equivalent to Maß +‎ -ig.
Derived from mehr (“more”).
From Middle High German meinunge, from Old High German meinunga. By surface analysis, meinen +‎ -ung. Compare Dutch mening and English meaning.
vocabList.usage:
Sie ist der Meinung, dass...
She is of the opinion that...

vocabList.etym: Literally, “with friendly greetings”. Akin to Dutch met vriendelijke groeten.
From Middle High German mugen, from Old High German mugan, from Proto-West Germanic *magan, from Proto-Germanic *maganą, from Proto-Indo-European *megʰ-.
From Middle High German natiurlich, from Old High German natūrlīh. Equivalent to Natur +‎ -lich. Compare Dutch natuurlijk, English naturally, Swedish naturlig.
From Middle High German nein, from a contraction of Old High German ni ein. Compare Old English nān, from ne ān (Modern English none, further contracted to no).
vocabList.usage:
Hast du morgen Abend Zeit? — Nein, leider nicht.
“Do you have time tomorrow night?” — “No, unfortunately not.”

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German niuwe, from Old High German niuwi, from Proto-West Germanic *niwi, from Proto-Germanic *niwjaz, from Proto-Indo-European *néwos.
From Middle High German niwiht, niweht, niht, a contracted form of Old High German niowiht, from nio (“never”) + wiht (“being, creature”), the last from Proto-Germanic *wihtą.
vocabList.usage:
Bitte nicht stören!
Please do not disturb!

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German nieman, from Old High German nioman; equivalent to nie (“never”) + Mann (“man”). Cognate with Dutch niemand, Afrikaans niemand, Low German nemann, nemand, nümand, Hunsrik nimmand.
From earlier Numero, from Italian numero, from Latin numerus (“number”). The feminine gender is probably due to the influence of Zahl f (“number”).

From Middle High German oder (whence also Yiddish אָדער (oder)), from Old High German odar, an alteration of odo by analogy with wedar (whence modern weder). The form odo is an assimilated, unstressed form of eddo (also edo), itself cognate with Old Saxon ettho, Old English eþþa, oþþe, Gothic 𐌰𐌹𐌸𐌸𐌰𐌿 (aiþþau). This formation is of uncertain origin: While the second component is Proto-Germanic *þau, the first may be *eh, *iþ (cf. Gothic 𐌹𐌸 (iþ)), or *jaba(i) (whence German ob, cf. Dutch ofte).
vocabList.usage:
Danach alles gestr. oder noch 1–2 Wörter?
Is everything after that crossed out or are there one or two more words?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German offen, Old High German offan, ofan, ophan, from Proto-West Germanic *opan. Cognate with Low German open, apen, Dutch open, English open, Danish åben, Swedish öppen. Related to auf.
From Middle High German offenen, from Old High German offanōn, from Proto-West Germanic *opanōn, from Proto-Germanic *upanōną. Compare Dutch openen and English open.
Borrowed from Italian prima.
Borrowed from Latin prō (“for”).
vocabList.usage:
Samt Mehrwertsteuer ergibt sich ein Kaufpreis von rund 30 Euro pro Stück
After VAT the price comes to around 30 euros each.

vocabList.etym: Borrowed from Italian per cento, from Latin per (“through, by”) and centum (“hundred”), modified by the influence of Latin pro (“for”) or German pro.
Partly via French qualité, partly directly from Latin qualitās. Compare Hunsrik Qualiteet.
vocabList.usage:
Unter Qualität versteht man die Gesamtheit aller Merkmale und Eigenschaften eines Gutes hinsichtlich seiner Eignung, festgelegte oder vorausgeschriebene Erfordernisse zu erfüllen.
Quality means the totality of features and characteristics of a good regarding its suitability to fulfil fixed or pre-written requirements.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ruowec (“quiet”). By surface analysis, Ruhe +‎ -ig.
From Middle High German runt, from Old French ront, from Latin rotundus (“round”) from rota (“wheel, disk”).

From earlier slecht, from Middle High German sleht, from Old High German sleht (see also schlicht), from Proto-Germanic *slihtaz. Cognate with English slight, Dutch slecht, Afrikaans sleg, Icelandic sléttur, Faroese slættur, Swedish slätt, Danish slet, Gothic 𐍃𐌻𐌰𐌹𐌷𐍄𐍃 (slaihts), and Norwegian slett.

From Middle High German slieȥen, from Old High German sliozan, from Proto-West Germanic *sleutan, from Proto-Germanic *slūtaną, *sleutaną (“to lock, shut”). Cognate with Old Saxon slūtan, Dutch sluiten, English slot.
vocabList.usage:
Das Geschäft schließt um 18.00 Uhr.
The store will close at 6 p.m.

vocabList.etym: schließen +‎ -lich
vocabList.usage:
Es freut mich, Sie schließlich zu treffen.
I'm glad to finally meet you.

vocabList.etym: From earlier slim, from Middle High German slimp (“slanting, awry”), from Old High German slimb, from Proto-West Germanic *slimb, from Proto-Germanic *slimbaz (“oblique, crooked”). Compare English slim (“thin”), Dutch slim (“clever, smart”), Middle Dutch slim (“bad, crooked”).
vocabList.usage: noch schlimmer ― even worse

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German sēr, from Old High German sēr (“sored, injured”), from Proto-West Germanic *sair. Compare Dutch zeer and English sorely for a similar semantic development.
vocabList.usage:
Ich bin sehr glücklich.
I am very happy.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German sīn, from Old High German sīn (“to be”), see Proto-Germanic *wesaną (“to be”) (suppleted with *beuną (“to be, exist, become”)), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁es- (“to be, exist”). Cognate with Dutch zijn (“to be”), Low German sien (“to be”).
Borrowed from Latin secunda. The units of time and angle are from pars minuta secunda (literally “second minute part”).
From so +‎ gar.
vocabList.usage:
Sogar Karl kann es verstehen.
Even Karl can understand it.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German scholn, schuln, from Old High German sculan, skulan, scolan, from Proto-West Germanic *skulan.

vocabList.usage:
Er spricht sowohl Deutsch als auch Englisch.
He speaks both German and English.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German tol, from Old High German tol, from Proto-West Germanic *dol, from Proto-Germanic *dulaz (“dazed, foolish, crazy, stupid”).

From Middle High German tuon, from Old High German tuon, from Proto-West Germanic *dōn, from Proto-Germanic *dōną, derived from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁- (“to put, set, place”). Cognate with English do.
über +‎ all. Compare English overall.
vocabList.usage:
Wir haben überall nach dem Ball gesucht.
We've looked for the ball everywhere.

vocabList.etym: From late Middle High German ūre, from Middle Low German ûre (“hour”), from Middle Dutch ure, from Old Dutch *ūra, from Old French houre, from Latin hōra, from Ancient Greek ὥρα (hṓra), from Proto-Indo-European *yeh₁- (“year, season”). The word was borrowed in the late 14th century when the diphthongization of -ū- into -ou-, -au- was already complete in most dialects; a shifted form exists, however, in dialects (compare Luxembourgish Auer). In German, the word early on developed the sense “timing device”, not present in other languages. Compare further Dutch uur, English hour, French heure. Doublet of Jahr.
un- +‎ möglich; cognate with Hunsrik unmeeghlich, Old Danish umugh(i)likær, Old Norse úmǫguligr, and Old Swedish ōmø̄gheliker
From verscheiden in its original sense of "separate, leave".
verzeihen +‎ -ung
From Old High German fiorteil. Equivalent to vier +‎ Teil.
From Middle High German vol, from Old High German foll, from Proto-West Germanic *full, from Proto-Germanic *fullaz, from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós.
From Middle High German wār, wǣre, from Old High German wār, wāri, from Proto-West Germanic *wār, from Proto-Germanic *wēraz.

From Middle High German wëhseln, from Old High German *wehsalōn, from Proto-Germanic *wihslōną, from Proto-Indo-European *weyk-, *weyḱ- (“to change”). Compare Dutch wisselen, Luxembourgish wiesselen, dialectal English wissle, more distantly Latin vicis, English week, German Woche.
From Old High German wīsa, from Proto-Germanic *wīsaz (“wise”).

From Middle High German weinec, wēnec (“marginal”), from Old High German *weinag, wēnag (“miserable”), from Proto-Germanic *wainagaz. The form with -ei- is original; that with -ē- arose through conflation with the morphologically simpler Old High German wē (“woe”), akin to English woe. The diphthong -ei- later on regularly became -ē- in several dialects, which further strengthened the monophthongal form wenig. Cognate with Dutch weinig, Low German weinig, Hunsrik wenich, Yiddish ווייניק (veynik).
From Middle High German wanne, wenne, from Old High German hwanne, hwenne, from Proto-West Germanic *hwan, similar to the adverb wann.
vocabList.usage:
Sag bitte Bescheid, wenn du fertig bist!
Tell me when you're done!

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wider, whence English widdershins via Middle Low German borrowing; from Old High German widar, from Proto-West Germanic *wiþr (“toward, against”). Cognate with English wither.
vocabList.usage:
Siehst du, jetzt hast du’s schon wieder gesagt!
See, now you’ve said it again!

vocabList.etym: wieder- +‎ holen

Inherited from Middle High German willekomen, from Old High German willechomen, from Proto-Germanic *wiljakumô. Cognate to Dutch welkom, English welcome, Danish velkommen, and other Germanic forms. Cognate with Portuguese bem-vindo, French bienvenu, Italian benvenuto, Spanish bienvenido, possibly Germanic calques.
vocabList.usage:
Du bist mir immer willkommen.
You’re always welcome to my house.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wullīn, wüllīn, from Old High German wullīn, from Proto-Germanic *wullīnaz (“woolen”), equivalent to Wolle +‎ -en.

From Middle High German wunderbære (also wunderberen, wunderberende), equivalent to Wunder +‎ -bar. Akin to German Low German wunnerbaar, Low German wunnerbor, Dutch wonderbaar, Saterland Frisian wunderboar, and also calques Danish, Norwegian Bokmål and Swedish underbar.

From Middle High German wunsch, from Old High German wunsc, from Proto-Germanic *wunskō, from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”). Compare Dutch wens, English wish, West Frisian winsk, Danish ønske.

From Middle High German wünschen, wunschen, from Old High German wunsken (“to choose, wish, desire”), from Proto-West Germanic *wunskijan (“to wish”), from Proto-Germanic *wunskijaną (“to wish”), derived from *wunskaz, *wunskō (“wish, desire”), from Proto-Indo-European *wun-, *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”). Cognate with Dutch wensen (“to wish”), English wish, Danish ønske (“to wish”), and further Sanskrit वांछ् (vāṃch, “to want”). Related to German Wonne (“lust, desire”). See also winsome, wone.
vocabList.usage:
Ich wünsche mir ein Meerschweinchen.
I want a guinea pig.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German zāle, from Old High German zala, from Proto-West Germanic *talu, from Proto-Germanic *talō, from Proto-Indo-European *dol- (“reckoning, calculation, fraud”), from Proto-Indo-European *del- (“to reckon, calculate”), cognate with Danish tal and Danish tale, Dutch taal, Low German Tahl, Hunsrik Zaal, English tale.
From Middle High German ziehen, from Old High German ziohan, from Proto-West Germanic *teuhan, from Proto-Germanic *teuhaną, from Proto-Indo-European *dewk- (“to pull, lead”).
From Middle High German zil, from Old High German zil, from Proto-West Germanic *til, from Proto-Germanic *tilą. Cognate to Old English til.

vocabList.definition: pretty, quite, rather, fairly, kind of
vocabList.etym: From Old High German zimilīh (“befitting”) or possibly directly from ziemen +‎ -lich.

From a spelling merger of two interrelated adpreps: 1.) Middle High German ze, from Old High German za, zi, from Proto-Germanic *ta; and 2.) Middle High German zuo, from Old High German zuo, from Proto-West Germanic *tō, from Proto-Germanic *tō.

Since ca. 1500, from univerbation of zu +‎ Frieden, literally “at peace”. Likely a calque of Middle Low German tô vrēde(n), Middle Dutch te vrēden (modern Dutch tevreden), both of which date from the 13th century. Apart from the dating, this is also confirmed by the fact that the earliest High German attestations are from Hesse and the Rhineland.
From Middle High German zuomachen, zuo machen, zūmachen, equivalent to zu- +‎ machen. Compare Middle Low German tômaken, whence German Low German tomaken.

From Middle High German ahtunge (“consideration, appreciation”), from Old High German ahtunga, from Proto-West Germanic *ahtungu. By surface analysis, achten +‎ -ung. Compare Yiddish אַכטונג (akhtung).

From Middle High German anelich, enlich (“alike”), from Old High German *analīh (attested in derivatives), a contraction of anagilīh, from Proto-Germanic *anagalīkaz, from *ana (“on”) + *galīkaz (“like”), that is “almost identical”. Compare German angleichen. Cognate with Middle Dutch aenlijck, English alike, Old Norse álíkr.
ahnen +‎ -ung
From Middle High German ūȥer, from Old High German ūȥar. More at aus. Cf. English outer, Norwegian uten-, ytre.
vocabList.usage:
Alle außer dir sind schon unterwegs.
Everyone except for you is already on their way.

vocabList.etym: äußere +‎ -st
From da +‎ mit. Compare English theremid, therewith, Dutch daarmee, Swedish därmed, Icelandic þar með.
Late 18th century, from ent- (“un-, dis-”) +‎ täuschen (“to deceive”), a calque of French détromper (“to disillusion”), which had earlier been borrowed as detrompi(e)ren (now obsolete).
From enttäusch- +‎ -t.
From Middle High German erklæren. By surface analysis, er- +‎ klären.
vocabList.usage:
Der Lehrer erklärte (mir) die quadratische Gleichung sehr gut.
The teacher explained the quadratic equation (to me) very well.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German genüegen, from Old High German ginuogen, from Proto-West Germanic *ganōgijan, from Proto-Germanic *ganōgijaną, from the adjective Proto-Germanic *ganōgaz (“enough, sufficient”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eh₂nóḱe (“he has reached, attained”), perfective of *h₂neḱ- (“to reach”). Cognate with Dutch genoegen, Icelandic nægja and Norwegian Nynorsk nøye.
vocabList.usage:
Wenige Regeln genügen für ein funktionierendes Spiel.
Few rules are enough for a functioning game.

vocabList.etym: From häuf(en) +‎ -ig.
Univerbation of heute +‎ zu +‎ Tage.
From Middle High German irren, from Old High German irren, from Proto-West Germanic *irʀijan, from Proto-Germanic *irzijaną.
vocabList.usage:
Wir sind eine Stunde durch die Stadt geirrt, weil wir das Hotel nicht gefunden haben.
We wandered around the city for an hour because we couldn't find the hotel.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German kūme, from Old High German kūmo, from Proto-Germanic *kūmaz, *kūmijaz (“weak, pitiful, frail”), from Proto-Indo-European *gewH- (“to call, cry”).[1] Cognate with English comely and archaic Dutch kuim (“barely”).
Univerbation of ob +‎ gleich, from the older use of ob as a conditional and concessive conjunction, reinforced with an adverb. Compare obwohl, obschon, obzwar and also gleichwohl.
From anstatt (“instead of”).
vocabList.usage:
Statt mich anzurufen, ging er mit seinen Freunden ins Kino.
Instead of calling me, he went to the movies with his friends.

vocabList.etym: um +‎ sonst, compare Danish omsonst.
voll +‎ -ig
Literally, “before everything”.

Chiefly a backformation from vorsichtig, from Middle High German vorsihtec, vürsihtec, from Old High German foresihtig, derived from foresiht, a calque of Latin providentia and provisio. By surface analysis, vor- +‎ Sicht. Doublet of Vorsehung. Although the noun must underlie the adjective, the former is not attested again (after Notker) before the 15th century; it remained rare until ca. 1650.  Compare Dutch voorzicht, English foresight.
From Middle High German wāgen, ultimately from Old High German wāga (“scales, balance; weight”) (see Waage), in the sense of putting something on the scales, not knowing where the balance will fall.
vocabList.usage: einen Versuch wagen ― to dare an attempt, to decide to make an attempt

vocabList.etym: From the present participle of währen (“to last, persist”), with rebracketing of währendes [noun], währender [noun], währendem [noun] as während des [noun], während der [noun], während dem [noun].
From Old High German wedar, from Proto-West Germanic *hwaþar, from Proto-Germanic *hwaþeraz; cognate with English whether and either.
vocabList.usage:
weder Himmel noch Hölle
neither heaven nor hell

vocabList.etym: Wert (“value”) +‎ voll (“full”)

From Middle High German zwāre, contraction of ze wāre (“verily, indeed”), from Old High German zi wāre (8th c.). Equivalent to zu + wahr.[1] The concessive use developed first in cognate Middle Low German twâre. Compare Czech sice.
vocabList.usage:
Dieser Rock ist zwar teuer, aber ich kaufe ihn trotzdem.
This skirt is admittedly expensive, but I’ll buy it anyway.

vocabList.etym: ab- +‎ trocknen
vocabList.usage:
Kannst du bitte das Geschirr abtrocknen?
Can you dry the dishes please?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German abewaschen, from Old High German abawaskan. Equivalent to ab- +‎ waschen.
From Middle High German anemachen. Equivalent to an- +‎ machen.
Compound of an- (“on, at”) +‎ ziehen (“pull”).
vocabList.usage:
Sie zieht sich sehr elegant an.
She dresses very elegantly.

vocabList.etym: auf- +‎ stehen
auf- (“up”) +‎ wachen (“to be awake”)
vocabList.usage:
Heute Morgen bin ich mit einem Kater aufgewacht.
This morning I woke up with a hangover.

vocabList.etym: Compound of aus +‎ ruhen.
vocabList.usage: sich auf seinen Lorbeeren ausruhen ― to rest on one's laurels

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ūzsehen. Analysable as aus- (“out”) +‎ sehen (“to see”). Compare Yiddish אויסזען (oyszen), Dutch uitzien, Norwegian Nynorsk sjå ut, Swedish se ut, Danish se ud.
From aus- (“out”) +‎ ziehen (“pull”).
vocabList.usage:
Unsere Abteilung muss bald aus den Büros in diesem Gebäude ausziehen.
Our department will soon have to vacate the offices in this building.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German backen, from Old High German backan, an originally weak verb and geminated variant of an older strong verb: Middle High German bachen, from Old High German bahhan, from Proto-West Germanic *bakan.
vocabList.usage:
Der Bäcker backt jeden Morgen 30 Laib Brot.
The baker bakes 30 loaves of bread every morning.

vocabList.etym: be- +‎ schreiben

From Middle High German buochstabe, from Old High German *buohstabo (“letter, writing”) (attested only as Old High German buohstab; > German Buchstab), from Proto-West Germanic *bōkstabō, from Proto-Germanic *bōkstabô, a variant of *bōkstabaz.[1] Compare English bookstaff, bookstave.
Back-formation from Bügeleisen (literally “iron with a bow, bail, handle”). By surface analysis, Bügel +‎ -en.
From Middle High German bürsten; see Borste (“brush, bristle”).
vocabList.usage:
Die Kacheln müsste ich mal richtig bürsten.
I have to properly brush these tiles sometime.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German īnslāfen. Equivalent to ein- +‎ schlafen.
From Middle High German hinlegen, from Old High German hinaleggen. Equivalent to hin- +‎ legen.
hin- +‎ setzen
vocabList.usage:
Ich möchte mich nicht auf den nassen Rasen hinsetzen.
I don’t want to sit down on the wet grass.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German keren, kern, from Old High German kerian, kerien, from Proto-Germanic *karjaną.
From Middle High German lēr, lēre, lǣre, from Old High German lāri, from Proto-West Germanic *lāʀi, from Proto-Germanic *lēziz. Cognate with Bavarian lar, Dutch laar, English leer.
leeren (weak, third-person singular present leert, past tense leerte, past participle geleert, auxiliary haben)
From Middle High German legen, from Old High German leggen, from Proto-West Germanic *laggjan, from Proto-Germanic *lagjaną.
vocabList.usage: Eier legen ― to lay eggs

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German liebe (“joy, affection, kindliness”), from Old High German liob, lioba (“fortune, health, pleasantness, joy”), from Proto-West Germanic *leubu (“love”). Related with Old High German luba, English love (from Proto-Germanic *lubō).

From Middle High German ligen, from Old High German ligen, from older liggen by generalisation of the stem of the 2nd and 3rd persons singular, from Proto-West Germanic *liggjan, from Proto-Germanic *ligjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *legʰ-.
From Middle High German mæjen, mæwen, from Old High German māen, from Proto-West Germanic *māan. Cognate with English mow.
From French organiser +‎ -ieren. Cognate with Hunsrik organiseere.

15th century, also in the form butzen. Origin unknown. Perhaps derived from Middle High German butze (“lump, piece, stump”), from Old High German *butz, from Proto-West Germanic *butt, from Proto-Germanic *buttaz (whence also English butt), with the interpretation of the verb being "to (remove) lumps and stumps", but there are several other theories.
From Middle High German sitzen, from Old High German sizzen, from Proto-West Germanic *sittjan. Cognate with Dutch zitten, Low German sitten, English sit, Danish sidde.
From Middle High German spüelen, from Old High German *spuolen (attested in Old High German irspuolen (“to wash”)), from Proto-West Germanic *spōlijan.
From Middle High German stecken, from Old High German steckōn, a geminated derivative of stehhan, whence modern stechen.

From Middle High German stān, stēn, from Old High German stān, stēn, from Proto-West Germanic *stān, from Proto-Germanic *stāną. The -h- was introduced into the spelling by analogy with sehen, in which it had become mute but was retained in spelling.
vocabList.usage:
Das Haus ist abgebrannt, aber die Wände stehen noch.
The house burned down, but the walls are still standing.

vocabList.definition:
: to put, place, positionsuch that it stands upright

 to pose, to lodge

to provide, to afford, to place at someone's disposal

to encounter and stop

to set, adjust
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German stellen, from Old High German stellen, from Proto-West Germanic *stalljan (“to put, position”), from Proto-Indo-European *stel- (“to place, put, post, stand”).
vocabList.usage:
Die Beklagte stellte den Antrag, die Klage abzuweisen.
The defendant lodged the application to reject the claim.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German teil, from Old High German teil, from Proto-West Germanic *daili, akin to Old Saxon dēl, cognate with English deal, Dutch deel, Low German Deil, Swedish del, Norwegian Bokmål del, Norwegian Nynorsk del, Danish del. Doublet of Deal.
vocabList.usage: zum großen Teil ― largely

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German and Old High German teilen, from Proto-West Germanic *dailijan (“to divide, part, deal”). Cognate with English deal.

From Middle High German trucken, trocken, from Old High German truckan, trokkan (“dried out, parched, thirsty, dry”), from Proto-West Germanic *drukn, from Proto-Germanic *druknaz, *druhnaz (“dry”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerǵʰ- (“to strengthen; become hard or solid”), from *dʰer- (“to hold, hold fast, support”).
vocabList.usage:
Ein Bier, bitte, meine Kehle ist ganz trocken.
A beer, please, my throat is really dry.

vocabList.etym: Deadjectival verb from trocken (“dry (adj.)”), i.e. trocken +‎ -en
um- +‎ ziehen
vor- +‎ bereiten
From Middle High German waschen, from Old High German wascan, waskan, from Proto-West Germanic *waskan.
vocabList.usage:
Wasch dir die Hände, bevor du zu Tisch gehst.
Wash your hands before you sit down to eat.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wecken, from Old High German wecchen, from Proto-West Germanic *wakkjan (“to wake up, to awaken”).
vocabList.usage:
Meine Katze ist zu mir ins Bett geklettert und hat mich aufgeweckt.
My cat crawled into my bed and woke me up.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wigen, a north-western variant of wegen, from generalisation of the latter's present singular forms (wige, wiges, wiget). Further from Old High German wegan, from Proto-West Germanic *wegan.
zu- +‎ nehmen
Unadapted borrowing from French adresse.
From Middle High German alter, from Old High German altar, from Proto-Germanic *aldrą. Cognate with German Low German Oller.

Inherited from Middle High German bart, from Old High German bart, from Proto-West Germanic *bard, from Proto-Germanic *bardaz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰardʰéh₂ (“beard”), possibly from *bʰers-.Compare Dutch baard, Luxembourgish Baart, West Frisian burd, English beard.
From Middle High German brille, berille, from berillus (“beryl”), from Latin beryllus (“beryl”). Compare dialectal English brills (“spectacles”).
Familie +‎ -n- +‎ Name
From Middle High German geboren, from Old High German giboran

First attested in the 11th century. From Middle High German heimuote, heimüete, from Old High German heimōti, heimuoti, from Proto-West Germanic *haimōdī (“homeland”). Compare Bavarian Hoamat, Silesian East Central German Heemte.
vocabList.usage:
Ich habe meine Heimat Türkei vor zwei Jahren verlassen.
I left my native Turkey two years ago.

vocabList.etym: Heim +‎ Fahrt
From Middle High German hīrāten, which is derived from Middle High German hīrāt (“marriage”), whence German Heirat (“marriage”).
From Middle High German lëdic, lëdec, from Old High German *lidig, from Proto-Germanic *liþugaz.
From lieb.

From Middle High German versprechen (“to guarantee”), from Old High German firsprehhan (“to defend verbally, to warrant”), from Proto-West Germanic *frasprekan. Analyzable as ver- +‎ sprechen. The sense “to misspeak” is a later transparent derivation (see the prefix).
vor- +‎ Name

From Middle High German alt, from Old High German alt, from Proto-West Germanic *ald, from Proto-Germanic *aldaz, from Proto-Indo-European *altós, *h₂eltós, from *h₂el- (“grow, nourish”). Compare Dutch oud, Low German old, West Frisian âld, English old. Doublet of Alt, a loanword from Italian.

an +‎ genehm, from Old High German nami,[1] ultimately from the same root as nehmen. Compare Sanskrit नमस्ते (namaste, “salutations (to you)”) for similar semantic development from the same Proto-Indo-European root.
Angst +‎ -lich
From Middle High German blode, from Old High German blōdi, from Proto-Germanic *blauþijaz, *blauþaz (“weak, soft, timid”).
From Middle High German dicke, from Old High German dicki, dicchi (akin to Old Saxon thikki), from Proto-West Germanic *þikkwī.
From German Low German doof (“deaf”), from Middle Low German dôf, from Old Saxon dof, from Proto-West Germanic *daub. Cognate to Upper German taub.
Inherited from Middle High German ērlich, from Old High German ērlīh, from Proto-West Germanic *aiʀulīk. Equivalent to Ehre (“honour”) +‎ -lich (“-ly”).
vocabList.usage:
Er hat sich sein Vermögen mit ehrlicher Arbeit verdient.
He earned his wealth by honest work.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German vlīzic, vlīzec, from Old High German flīzīg. By surface analysis, Fleiß +‎ ig.
From Middle High German vröude, from Old High German frouwida, frewida, from Proto-Germanic *frawiþō (“joy”), derived from *frawaz (“joyous”), from Proto-Indo-European *prew- (“to jump; hop”).
vocabList.usage:
Große Freude kommt auf.
Great joy is erupting.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German vriuntlich, vrūntlich, friuntlich, from Old High German friuntlīh, from Proto-Germanic *frijōndlīkaz, equivalent to Freund +‎ -lich. Cognate with Dutch vriendelijk, English friendly.
From Middle High German vorhtebære. Equivalent to Furcht +‎ -bar.
From Middle High German gedultic, from Old High German gidultig; By surface analysis, Geduld +‎ -ig. Cognates include Dutch geduldig and Old English geþyldig.
vocabList.usage:
Sei geduldig, das braucht Zeit.
Be patient, this takes time.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gevallen, from Old High German gifallan.[1] Equivalent to ge- (expressing the terminative aspect) +‎ fallen.
From Gemüt +‎ -lich.
vocabList.usage:
Die neue Couch ist sehr gemütlich.
The new couch is very cosy.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German grōȥ, from Old High German grōȥ, akin to Old Saxon grōt, compare Dutch groot. More at English great.
From Middle High German grœze, from Old High German grōzī, from Proto-Germanic *grautį̄. Analysable as groß +‎ -e.
From Middle High German hazzen, from Old High German hazzōn, from Proto-Germanic *hatāną.
From Middle High German hezzelich, hazzelich, hazlich, hezlich, from Old High German hazlīh. Equivalent to Hass +‎ -lich.
By surface analysis, Hilfe +‎ bereit.
From Middle High German hübesch (“courtly”), from the root of modern Hof (“court”). Cognate with Yiddish היפּש (hipsh).

Inherited from Middle High German klein, kleine, from Old High German kleini, from Proto-West Germanic *klainī (“shining, fine, splendid, tender”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *gleh₁y- (“to cleave, stick”).

From Middle High German kluoc, which was borrowed via the Lower Rhineland from Middle Low German klōk and Middle Dutch cloec, from Proto-Germanic *klōkaz. Compare Old Norse klókr, and dialectal Dutch kloek.

Early 16th century in the sense “comedic”, directly from Latin comicus + -isch, from Ancient Greek κωμικός (kōmikós). The broader sense “funny” since the 17th century under influence of French comique. The sense “strange” was derived thence (as in English funny).

Via Middle High German lūne (“moon, changing mood, disposition”), borrowed from Latin lūna (“moon”). The semantic association of "moon" to "mood" is based on the similarity of the changing phases of the moon to the changing moods of a person (DWDS).
vocabList.usage:
Du hast heute gute Laune.
You're in a good mood today.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German lūt, from Old High German lūt, akin to Old Saxon hlūd, from Proto-West Germanic *hlūd.
From an earlier lockicht, from Middle High German lockeht, analyzable as Locke (“curl”) +‎ -ig.
From Middle High German lustec, from Old High German lustīg. By surface analysis, Lust (“pleasure, joy; wish”) +‎ -ig (“-y”).
From mittel- (“medium, average”) +‎ groß (“large, tall”).
From Middle High German müede, muode, from Old High German muodi, from Proto-West Germanic *mōþī. Cognate to Dutch moe.
vocabList.usage:
Die müden Kinder gingen ins Bett.
The tired children went to bed.

vocabList.etym: From Latin nervōsus, equivalent to Nerv +‎ -ös.
From Middle Dutch net (“neat, decent, pretty”), from Old French net (“neat, decent”), from Latin nitidus. Compare English neat.
Equivalent to ordnen (“to put in order”) +‎ -lich.
From Middle High German pech, bech, from Old High German peh, beh, from Proto-West Germanic *pik (“pitch, tar, wood resin”).

From Middle High German rīche, from Old High German rīhhi (“rich, mighty”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīkī, from Proto-Germanic *rīkijaz, a derivative of *rīks (“king, ruler”), itself a borrowing from Proto-Celtic *rīxs (compare Irish rí).[1] All from Proto-Indo-European *h₃reǵ- (“to rule”), from which Latin rēx is derived. See also German Reich.
From Middle High German sat, from Old High German sat, from Proto-West Germanic *sad, from Proto-Germanic *sadaz, from Proto-Indo-European *seh₂-. Compare Dutch zat, English sad, Danish sat.
vocabList.usage:
Willst du noch was? − Nein danke, ich bin satt.
Do you want some more? – No thanks, I'm done.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German sūber, from Old High German sūbar, from Proto-West Germanic *sūbrī, from Latin sobrius (“sober”).

From Middle High German scharpf, from Old High German scarf, from Proto-West Germanic *skarp, from Proto-Germanic *skarpaz, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kerb-, from *(s)ker- (“to cut”). Compare Low German scharp, Dutch scherp, English sharp, Danish skarp.
From French chic, itself from German Schick (“correct manners, correct clothing”).
From Middle High German slanc, Middle Low German slank, ultimately related to Proto-Germanic *slingwaną (“to twist, wind”), the source of schlingen.
From Schmutz +‎ -ig, whence also dialectal Dutch smotsig. Compare also English smutty.

Borrowed from Middle Low German schüchter, whence also Dutch schuchter. Cognate with scheu. The final -n is an original case ending, which was sometimes added to the stem in Low German (compare German albern).
From Middle High German starc, from Old High German stark, from Proto-West Germanic *stark.

From Middle High German strenge, from Old High German strengi (“strong”), strangi, from Proto-Germanic *strangijaz (“tight, tense”), *strangaz, from Proto-Indo-European *strengʰ- (“taut”); related to Proto-Indo-European *ster- (“stiff”). Cognate with Dutch streng, English strong, Danish streng.

From Middle High German tōt, from Old High German tōt, from Proto-West Germanic *daud, from Proto-Germanic *daudaz. Compare Dutch dood, Middle Low German dôt, English dead, Danish død, Norwegian Nynorsk daud.

From Middle High German trūrec, from Old High German trūrag, from Proto-Germanic *dreuzagaz (“bloody”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰreus- (“to break, break off, crumble”). Cognate with Dutch treurig (“sad, gloomy”), Low German trurig (“sad”), Hunsrik traurich (“sad”), English dreary (“grievous, dire, appalling, drab, dark, colourless, cheerless”), Old Norse dreyrigr (“bloody”).
un- (“un-”) +‎ ordentlich (“tidy”)

From Middle High German verstān, virstēn, vorstēn, ferstān, from Old High German firstān, firstēn, from Proto-Germanic *frastāną, equivalent to ver- +‎ stehen. Cognate with Bavarian versteh, Dutch verstaan, Middle Low German vorstān. Compare also English forstand.
vocabList.usage:
Ich verstehe dich nicht bei dem Lärm.
I can't understand you with this noise.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German anzuc, verbal noun of aneziehen. Equivalent to an- +‎ Zug.
From Arm +‎ Band.
Initialism of Büstenhalter or Busenhalter.
Borrowed from French blouse.
From Middle High German gürtel, from Old High German gurtil, from Proto-West Germanic *gurdil, from Proto-Germanic *gurdilaz (“girdle, belt”). By surface analysis, gürten +‎ el.
From Middle High German *halskette, from Old High German halsketinna (“neck shackle”). Equivalent to Hals (“neck”) +‎ Kette (“chain”); cognate with Dutch halsketting.

Inherited from Middle High German hantschuoch, from Old High German hantscuoh, from Proto-West Germanic *handuskōh. Equivalent to Hand (“hand”) +‎ Schuh (“shoe”). Cognate with Bavarian Håndschuach, German Low German Handsch, Handschoh, Hansch, Luxembourgish Händsch, Dutch handschoen, Danish handske, Norwegian Bokmål hanske, Norwegian Nynorsk hanske, handske (obsolete), Swedish handske, Faroese handski, Icelandic hanski, hanzki (obsolete).
From Hand (“hand”) +‎ Tasche (“bag”).
From Middle High German hemde, hemede, from Old High German hemidi (“skin”), from Proto-West Germanic *hamiþi (“shirt”).
From Middle High German hose, from Old High German hosa, from Proto-West Germanic *hosā.

From Middle High German huot, from Old High German huot, from Proto-West Germanic *hōd, from Proto-Germanic *hōdaz, possibly from a Proto-Indo-European *kadʰ- (“to protect”), but the existence of such a root is doubtful. Cognate to Dutch hoed, English hood.
From Middle French jaque, originally a peasant garment, from the name Jacques (“James”), considered a typical peasant's name.
First borrowed in the early 18th century directly from Italian costume, which see. Later influenced by French costume, itself also from the Italian.
Borrowed from French cravate. Compare English cravat and Spanish corbata. Doublet of Kroate (“Croat”).

An originally Low and Central German form (though not in all dialects of the latter). From Middle Low German lippe and northern Middle High German lippe, from Old High German *lippa, from Proto-West Germanic *lippjō.
From Middle High German mantel, from Old High German mantal, from Late Latin mantellum, diminutive of mantum, ultimately from Gaulish.
Borrowed from French mode.
From Middle High German almuʒ, ultimately from Medieval Latin almutia (“hood, cowl”), of unknown origin. Compare Latin amictus (“clothed, veiled”).
Inherited from Middle High German naht, from Old High German naht, from Proto-West Germanic *naht, from Proto-Germanic *nahts, from Proto-Indo-European *nókʷts.
vocabList.usage:
Die Nacht war lang und frostig.
The night was long and chilly.

vocabList.etym: Borrowed from French parfum, ultimately from Latin per (“through”) + fūmum, the accusative singular of fūmus (“smoke, steam, fume”).
Clipping of Pullover  +‎ -i.

From Middle High German roc, from Old High German roc, from Proto-West Germanic *hrokk, from Proto-Germanic *hrukkaz, from Proto-Indo-European *rukn-, *ruk-, *rug-, *ruǵ- (“to spin”); or perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *kreḱ- (“to weave”). Doublet of Frack.
Borrowed from English shawl, from Persian شال (šâl).
schlafen (“sleep”) +‎ Anzug (“clothes, suit”)
Formally from English slip (“kind of underskirt”), but with the sense of etymologically related German Schlüpfer, also Schlüpper (“briefs, panties”).

From Middle High German socke, from Old High German soc, a West Germanic borrowing from Latin soccus (“a light shoe or slipper, buskin”), from Ancient Greek σύκχος (súkkhos, “a kind of shoe”), probably from Phrygian or from an Anatolian language.
From Middle High German stivel, from Old High German stival, borrowed from  Old French estivel, perhaps from Latin aestas (“summer”) or Latin stipes (“tree trunk, log”).
From Strumpf (“stocking”) +‎ Hose (“trousers”).

From Middle High German tasche, from Old High German taska, tasca. Further origin unknown. Perhaps from Proto-Germanic *taskǭ. Cognate with Dutch tas, Hunsrik Tasch, Middle Low German tasche (“bag, pouch”), Old Norse taska (“bag, purse”) (probably borrowed from Low German). Compare English tasse (“plate armor, which protects the thighs”).
From Middle High German tragen, from Old High German tragan, from Proto-West Germanic *dragan, from Proto-Germanic *draganą (“to draw, drag”).
vocabList.usage:
Sie konnten die Kiste nicht mehr tragen und mussten sie abstellen.
They couldn't carry the box any longer and had to put it down.

vocabList.etym: Training +‎ -s- +‎ Anzug (“suit”)
From unter- (“under”) +‎ Hose (“trousers”). Cognate with Hunsrik Unnerhoss.
unter- +‎ Wäsche
From Arbeit (“work”) +‎ -s- +‎ Zimmer (“room”).
From backen +‎ Ofen.
baden (“to bathe”) +‎ Wanne (“tub”)
From baden (“to bath”) +‎ Zimmer (“room”).
From Bücher +‎ Regal.

From Middle High German buode, from Old High German *buoda, from Proto-West Germanic *bōþu, from Proto-Germanic *bōþō. Probably related to *būaną (“to build”), whence German bauen.[1] Cognate with Middle Dutch boede, Middle Low German bôde, Old Norse búð, bóð, whence English booth.
From Middle High German decke, from Old High German theckī, decchī, derived from thecken (modern decken), from Proto-West Germanic *þakkjan, from Proto-Germanic *þakjaną.
vocabList.usage:
unter einer Decke stecken
to be in cahoots
(literally, “be under the same blanket”)

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German dille, from Old High German dilla, from Proto-Germanic *þiljǭ. More at thill.
From doppel- (“double”) +‎ Haus (“house”).
From French douche, from Italian doccia. The word became much more common after World War II, as the native word Brausebad had developed bad connotations.
See Dusche.
vocabList.usage:
Ich dusche (mich) jeden Tag.
I shower every day.

vocabList.etym: eine (“one”) +‎ Familie (“family”) +‎ -n- +‎ Haus (“house”)
vocabList.usage:
Peter besitzt ein Einfamilienhaus.
Peter owns a family home.

vocabList.etym: Erde +‎ Geschoss
From essen (“eat”, verb) +‎ Zimmer (“room”).
From Middle High German vluor, from Old High German fluor, from Proto-Germanic *flōraz.
From Fuß (foot) +‎ Boden (bottom, ground, floor).
From Middle High German garte, from Old High German garto, from Proto-West Germanic *gardō.
From Gas (“gas”) +‎ Herd (“cooker, stove”).
Haar +‎ Bürste
From Middle High German hanttuoch, from Old High German hanttuoh. By surface analysis, Hand (“hand”) +‎ Tuch (“cloth”).
From heizen +‎ Körper.
heizen (“to heat”) +‎ -ung (nominal suffix to form nouns from verbs)
vocabList.usage:
Dreh die Heizung auf.
turn the heat up.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German kamb, camb, chamb, from Old High German chamb, from Proto-West Germanic *kamb, from Proto-Germanic *kambaz, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵómbʰos (“tooth”).
From Middle High German kemben, kemmen, from Old High German kemben, kempen, from Proto-Germanic *kambijaną (“to comb”).
vocabList.usage:
Ich kämme dir kurz die Haare.
I’ll comb / brush your hair quickly.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German keller, from Old High German kellari, from Proto-West Germanic *kellārī (“cellar, storeroom”). See Kellner.
From the verb klingen.
Shortened from Klosett.
From Middle High German knopf, from Old High German knopf, from Proto-Germanic *knuppaz (“lump, clod”). Cognate with Hunsrik Knopp, Luxembourgish Knapp, Dutch knoop.
Borrowed from French commode.
Compound of kühl (“cool”) +‎ Schrank (“cabinet”).
From Middle High German lampe, from Latin lampada, from Latin lampas. Cognate with English lamp.

From Middle High German lieht (Middle German also līcht), from Old High German lioht, from Proto-West Germanic *leuht, from Proto-Germanic *leuhtą, from Proto-Indo-European *lewktom. Compare Dutch licht, English light.
Mikrowelle (“micro wave”) +‎ Herd (“oven”)
15th century, from Middle French meuble(s) (“household goods”), from Latin mobilis. At first restricted to the Moselle region, more widely attested since ca. 1600.
Möbel +‎ -iert
From Middle High German oben, obene, from Old High German obana, from Proto-West Germanic *obanā, from Proto-Germanic *ubanē. Related to über and ober-.

From north-eastern Middle High German rase, probably from Middle Low German wrāse (“sod, turf”), though the two could also be cognate forms. Further origin presumably a variant of Middle Low German wāse, from Old Saxon waso, from Proto-West Germanic *wasō (“moisture, slime, muck”) which has been inherited as German Wasen.[1]
Early 17th century, of unclear origin. Hypotheses include:[1]
From Schlaf (“sleep”) +‎ Zimmer (“room”).

From Middle High German slüȥȥel, from Old High German sluȥȥil, from Proto-West Germanic *slutil, which is derived from *sleutan (“to close”), from which also modern German schließen.
Cognate with Dutch sleutel and English slot.[1]
vocabList.usage:
Der Schlüssel passt nicht.
The key doesn't fit.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German seife, from Old High German seifa, seiffa, from Proto-Germanic *saipǭ, from Proto-Indo-European *seyb- (“to pour out, dribble, strain, trickle”). Cognate with Dutch zeep, Low German Seep, West Frisian sjippe, English soap.
From French sofa and Italian sofà, from Arabic صُفَّة (ṣuffa).
From spülen (“rinse, wash”) +‎ Becken (“basin”).
From spülen (“to wash”) +‎ Maschine (“machine”).
From steppen +‎ Decke.
From Middle High German stoc, from Old High German stoc, from Proto-West Germanic *stokk.
vocabList.usage:
Ich weiß nicht, wo ich den Stock gelassen habe; haben Sie ihn nicht gesehen?
I don't know where I've left the staff; haven't you seen it?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German stuofe, from Old High German stuofa, from Proto-West Germanic *stōpā, related to the verb *stappjan (“to tread, step”).

Borrowed from French tablette.
Doublet of Tablet

15th century. From Medieval Latin tapēta f (“wall covering”), from the plural of tapētum n, itself derived from tapēte n, tapēs m, from Ancient Greek τάπης m (tápēs, “carpet, rug”), from an Iranian word.
From Middle High German teppich, tepich, teppech, tepech, tepch, teppch; from Old High German teppih, tepich, teppech; from Medieval Latin tapicus; from Latin tapes.
tiefkühlen (“to freeze”) +‎ Truhe (“chest”)
Tisch +‎ Tuch
From Toilette (“toilet”) +‎ -n- +‎ Papier (“paper”).

From Middle High German topf, from Old High German *topf, from Proto-West Germanic *dopp, from Proto-Germanic *duppaz (“hollow, bowl”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewb- (“deep, hollow”). Cognate with Dutch dop (“little cup, thimble”), Low German Dopp (“shell, pod, bowl”), Saterland Frisian Dop (“shell, pod, bowl”), English dop (“cup in which a diamond is cut”).
Attested since the 12th century, from Middle High German treppe, trappe, from Old High German trappa, from Proto-West Germanic *trappā.
From Middle High German tuoch, from Old High German tuoh, from Proto-West Germanic *dōk (“cloth”). Compare Dutch doek (“cloth, canvas”), English duck. More at duck, dook.
From Middle High German, from Old High German turi, from Proto-West Germanic *dur. Compare English door.
From Middle High German unden(e), undenen, und(e)nân, untnân, from Old High German undenân, untenân, untana. Related to unter.
From Middle High German vorhanc, vürhanc. By surface analysis, deverbal from vorhängen.
waschen +‎ Becken

From Middle High German wesche, from Old High German wesca, from Proto-West Germanic *waski ~ *waskiju (not attested outside High German). Cognate with Luxembourgish Wäsch, Vilamovian weś, etc. With a different stem formation compare Dutch was, Old High German wasca. By surface analysis, waschen (“to wash”) +‎ -e.
vocabList.usage:
Nach der Wäsche muss ich meine Hemden bügeln.
After washing I need to iron my shirts.

vocabList.etym: From waschen (“to wash, to launder”) +‎ Küche (“kitchen”)
From waschen (“to wash”) +‎ Maschine (“machine”).
From Wasser +‎ Hahn.
wecken (“to wake”) +‎ -er (suffix forming agent nouns)
From wohnen +‎ Zimmer.

From Middle High German brief, from Old High German briaf, which is borrowed from Latin breve, a neuter form of brevis (“short”). Cognates include Middle Dutch brief, Dutch brief, Old Norse bréf, Old Saxon brēf (all of them borrowed from Latin)[1][2] and English brief.
Brief (“letter”) +‎ Freund (“friend”)
From Middle High German bruoder, from Old High German bruoder, from Proto-West Germanic *brōþer, from Proto-Germanic *brōþēr, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰréh₂tēr. Doublet of Frater.
Ca. 1600, from Middle French cousin, from Latin consobrinus.
From French dame, from Latin domina (“mistress, lady”). Cognate with English dame.
From Ehe (“marriage”) +‎ Frau (“woman”).
From Middle High German eltern, from Old High German eltirōn, from Proto-Germanic *alþizô. Compare Dutch ouders, English elders.
From Middle High German enkel, from Old High German enkil, enchil, Proto-West Germanic *ankil, *ankul, from Proto-Germanic *ankulaz (“ankle”). Cognate with Dutch enkel, English ankle.
Nominalization of erwachsen.
Borrowed from Latin familia

From Middle High German vrouwe, from Old High German frouwa (“mistress”), from Proto-West Germanic *frauwjā, from Proto-Germanic *frawjǭ, a feminine form of *frawjô (“lord”), giving Old English frēa (“lord, king; God, Christ; husband”), frēo (“woman”), from Proto-Indo-European *proHwo-, a derivation from *per- (“to go forward”).
Middle High German vrouwelīn (“mistress, young unmarried noblewoman”), equivalent to Frau +‎ -lein

Inherited from Middle High German vriunt, from Old High German friunt, from Proto-West Germanic *friund, from Proto-Germanic *frijōndz (“lit., the loving one; lover, loved one, friend”), from a derivative of Proto-Indo-European *preyH-.

From Middle High German geswister, from Old High German giswëstar, equivalent to ge- +‎ Schwester. Compare Old Saxon gisustrōni (“sibling”), Old Frisian swesterne, susterne, sisterne (“siblings”), Old English ġesweostren (“maternal cousin, sister”).

From groß +‎ Vater. Cognate to Dutch grootvader, German Low German Grautvader (Paderbornisch). Displaced Middle High German eltervater, altervater (“grandfather”). Compare English grandfather, which displaced English eldfather, elderfather in a similar manner.
Fixed nominalisation of Middle High German jung (“young”), from Old High German jung (“young”).
From Middle High German liute, from Old High German liuti, also liudi, from Proto-West Germanic *liud(i), from Proto-Germanic *liudīz (“people”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁lewdʰ- (“man, people”).

From Middle High German magedichīn, meidichīn, from Old High German *magadihhīn or calqued from Middle Low German mēgedeken, megedekīn, both from Proto-West Germanic *magaþukīn. Equivalent to Magd +‎ -chen.

From Middle High German manlich, from Old High German manlīh, manalīh, from Proto-West Germanic *mannlīk, from Proto-Germanic *mannlīkaz. By surface analysis, Mann +‎ lich. Cognates include Dutch mannelijk, English manly, and Old Norse mannligr (“human”) (whence Danish mandlig, Swedish manlig).

From Middle High German muoter, from Old High German muoter, from Proto-West Germanic *mōder, from Proto-Germanic *mōdēr, from Proto-Indo-European *méh₂tēr. Compare Dutch moeder, English mother, Danish moder, Swedish moder.

From Middle High German nāchgebūr(e), from Old High German nāhgibūr(o), from Proto-West Germanic *nāhwagabūrō, from Proto-Germanic *nēhwagabūrô (“neighbour”). Equivalent to nah, nach (“near, next, after”) + Bauer (“dweller, farmer”).

From Middle High German neve, from Old High German nefo, nevo, from Proto-West Germanic *nefō, from Proto-Germanic *nefô. Cognate with Dutch neef, obsolete English neve. Further from Proto-Indo-European *népōts, whence English nephew, which see for more.
Borrowed from Middle Low German nichte, from Old Saxon *nifta, from Proto-Germanic *niftiz.
Borrowed from French oncle.
Cognate with Dutch opa. This etymology is incomplete. You can help Wiktionary by elaborating on the origins of this term.
From Middle High German swëster, from Old High German swëster, from Proto-Germanic *swestēr.
From Middle High German sun, from Old High German sunu, from Proto-West Germanic *sunu, from Proto-Germanic *sunuz, from Proto-Indo-European *suHnús.
Borrowed from French tante.
Tochter f (genitive Tochter, plural Töchter, diminutive Töchterchen n or Töchterlein n)

From Middle High German vater, from Old High German fater, from Proto-West Germanic *fader, from Proto-Germanic *fadēr, from Proto-Indo-European *ph₂tḗr. Germanic cognates include Dutch vader, Low German Vader, English father, Danish fader, Gothic 𐍆𐌰𐌳𐌰𐍂 (fadar).
vocabList.usage:
Mein Vater erklärt mir jeden Sonntag unsere neun Planeten.
My father explains to me our nine planets every Sunday.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wīplich, from Old High German wīblīh, from Proto-Germanic *wībalīkaz, equivalent to Weib +‎ -lich. Cognate with Dutch wijfelijk, English wifely.
vocabList.usage:
Sie gehört dem weiblichen Geschlecht an.
She belongs to the female sex.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ente, confluence of (1.) the plural and oblique singular of ant and (2.) the Old High German variant enita, both from older anut, from Proto-West Germanic *anad. Cognate with Dutch eend.
From Middle High German vrëȥȥen, from Old High German frëȥȥan, firëȥȥan, from Proto-West Germanic *fraetan. Cognate with Dutch vreten, English fret, Gothic 𐍆𐍂𐌰𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽 (fraitan), Swedish fräta.

From Middle High German vüetern, from Old High German fuotiren, derived from fuotar, from Proto-Germanic *fōdrą (“fodder”). Equivalent to Futter +‎ -n. Compare Dutch voeren (“to feed”), dialectal English to fodder.
From Middle High German has(e), from Old High German haso, from Proto-West Germanic *hasō, from Proto-Germanic *hasô, from an Indo-European root originally meaning grey.
Inherited from Middle High German hunt.

From Middle Low German kanīneken, diminutive of kanīn, konīn, itself probably through Middle Dutch connijn from Old French connin, northern variant of connil, from Latin cunīculus. Analysable as Kanin +‎ -chen. Compare English cony.
Inherited from Middle High German katze, Old High German kazza, from Proto-West Germanic *kattā. Akin to Old English catt (“cat”).
Inherited from Middle High German kuo.
From Meer (“sea”) +‎ Schwein (“pig, swine”) +‎ -chen (diminutive suffix), literally “little sea pig”, or from Meerschwein +‎ -chen. The use of Meer refers to the animal as coming from overseas.

From Middle High German phert, phærît, pherit, pferift (“riding horse”), from Old High German pherit, pfarifrit, parafred, from Late Latin paraverēdus (originally “substitute post horse”). Largely displaced the native word Ross. Compare Dutch paard and English palfrey.
vocabList.usage:
Meine Mutter hat ein Pferd und das ist sehr süß.
My mother has a horse and it is very cute.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German schâf, from Old High German scāf.
By surface analysis, compound of Schild (“shield”) +‎ Kröte (“toad”).

From Middle High German slange, from Old High German slango, from Proto-Germanic *slangô. Cognate with German Low German Slang (“snake”), Dutch slang (“snake”), West Frisian slang (“snake”). Compare also Albanian shlligë (“adder”).
From Middle High German tier, from Old High German tior, from Proto-West Germanic *deuʀ, from Proto-Germanic *deuzą, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewsóm. Cognate to English deer.

From Middle High German vogel, vagel, from Old High German fogal, fugal, from Proto-West Germanic *fugl, from Proto-Germanic *fuglaz; possibly related to *fleuganą (“to fly”) through dissimilation from earlier *fluglaz. Cognates include Low German Vagel, Dutch vogel, English fowl, Danish fugl, Swedish fågel, Gothic 𐍆𐌿𐌲𐌻𐍃 (fugls).
From Welle (“wave”) +‎ Sittich (“parakeet”), a calque of translingual Melopsittacus undulatus.
17th century, from backen +‎ Stein, a calque of Middle Low German backstên.

From Middle High German boumwolle, from Late Old High German boumwolla. By surface analysis, Baum (“tree”) +‎ Wolle (“wool”). Perhaps based on Herodotus’ description of wool-bearing trees in India; compare Ancient Greek ἐριόξυλον (erióxulon, “cotton”, literally “wood/tree-wool”) and Latin linum xylinum (“cotton”, literally “wood/tree-flax”).
Compound of Kunst +‎ Stoff.
From Middle High German lëder, from Old High German lëdar, from Proto-West Germanic *leþr, from Proto-Germanic *leþrą (“leather”). Akin to Old Saxon lethar.
From Middle High German metalle, from Latin metallum (14th century).
From Middle High German sīde, from Old High German sīda, from Proto-West Germanic *sīdā (“silk”), from sēta (“silk”), from Latin saeta (“horsehair; bristle; silk”).
From Middle High German stein, from Old High German stein, from Proto-West Germanic *stain, from Proto-Germanic *stainaz (“stone”), ultimately from the Proto-Indo-European root *steyh₂-.

First attested in the mid 17th century. Most likely borrowed from Early Modern Dutch stof, from Middle Dutch stoffe, borrowed from Old French estophe, estoffe, from estoffer (“to provide what is necessary, equip, stuff”). The word is ultimately Germanic and was borrowed into Old French from Old High German stoffōn, itself from Proto-West Germanic *stoppōn, making it a doublet of stopfen (“to stuff, to plug”).
From Middle High German wolle, from Old High German wolla, from Proto-West Germanic *wullu.
From Middle High German blā (genitive blāwes), from Old High German blāo, from Proto-West Germanic *blāu, from Proto-Germanic *blēwaz.

From Middle High German bunt, probably from Latin punctus, whence also English point; this would make it a doublet of Punkt. Dutch bont seems to have somewhat earlier attestations in the relevant sense, but the phonetic form (b- for p- and Dutch -o- for -u-) could hint at Middle High German origin. It is therefore unsettled which of the two borrowed from which.
From Middle High German grā, from Old High German grāo, from Proto-West Germanic *grāu. Compare English gray, grey.
From Middle High German grüene, from Old High German gruoni, gruoen, from Proto-West Germanic *grōnī, from Proto-Germanic *grōniz. Compare Low German grön, Dutch groen, English green, Danish grøn.
From French lilas.
From Latin rosa.

From Middle High German rōt (“red, red-haired”), from Old High German rōt (“red, scarlet, purple-red, brown-red, yellow-red”), from Proto-West Germanic *raud, from Proto-Germanic *raudaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rowdʰós, from *h₁rewdʰ-.
From Middle High German swarz, from Old High German swarz, from Proto-West Germanic *swart, from Proto-Germanic *swartaz, from Proto-Indo-European *swerd- (“dirty, dark, black”).
alt (“old”) +‎ modisch (“fashionable”)
From Middle High German endern, more at anderer (“other, different”). Cognate with Hunsrik ennre.
vocabList.usage:
Früher dachte ich, Botanik sei langweilig, aber ich habe meine Meinung geändert.
I used to think Botany was boring, but I've changed my opinion.

vocabList.etym: an- +‎ probieren
From Middle High German anrihte, from the verb anrihten (“to prepare”); see anrichten for more.
an- +‎ schalten
ärgern +‎ -lich
vocabList.usage:
Der unerwartete Kurseinbruch war sehr ärgerlich für die Anleger.
The unexpected decline in share prices was very annoying for investors.

vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German argern (“worsen”), from Old High German argerōn, derived from arg (“bad”). Compare English eerie.
vocabList.usage:
Die anderen Kinder ärgern ihn immer.
The other kids keep annoying him.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ertec. Equivalent to Art +‎ -ig.
From Middle High German ūfsliezen. Equivalent to auf- +‎ schließen.
aus- +‎ schlafen
From Middle High German begiezen, from Old High German bigiozan, from Proto-West Germanic *bigeutan. Equivalent to be- +‎ gießen.
From Middle High German bīȥen, from Old High German bīȥan, from Proto-West Germanic *bītan, from Proto-Germanic *bītaną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰéydt (“to split”).
From beziehen +‎ -ung.
From Middle High German brūt, from Old High German brūt (akin to Old Saxon brūd), from Proto-West Germanic *brūdi, from Proto-Germanic *brūdiz. Compare Dutch bruid, English bride, Danish brud.
Compound of Dach (“roof”) +‎ Boden (“floor, ground”).
From Middle High German ē, ēwe, from Old High German ēwa, from Proto-West Germanic *aiw, from Proto-Germanic *aiwǭ, *aiwaz (“law, custom”).
From Middle High German eigenschaft, from Old High German eiganscaft, eiganskaft, equivalent to eigen (“own”, adjective) +‎ -schaft (“-ship”).
From Middle High German erschīnen, from Old High German irskīnan, from Proto-West Germanic *uʀskīnan. Equivalent to er- +‎ scheinen.
From Fenster +‎ Laden.
From fern (“far”) +‎ Bedienung (“handling, operation”).
From Middle High German vriuntschaft, from Old High German friuntscaf, from Proto-West Germanic *friundskapi. Equivalent to Freund (“friend”) +‎ -schaft (“-ship”).
From Gebrauch (“use”) +‎ -s- +‎ Anweisung (“instruction, direction”).
From Middle High German gevāre, gevære, from Old High German fāra, from Proto-Germanic *fērō. Cognate with English fear and Dutch gevaar.
See the verb scheiden (“to separate”)
From Middle High German wiht, gewiht, from Old High German giwihti, ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *gawihtī. Compare Dutch gewicht, Danish vægt, English weight, Swedish vikt.
From Middle High German grif, from Old High German grif, from Proto-West Germanic *gripi, from Proto-Germanic *gripiz.
Inherited from Middle High German güetec. By surface analysis, Güte (“kindness”) +‎ -ig. Cognate with Dutch goedig.
From Middle High German heizen, from Old High German heizen, from Proto-West Germanic *haitijan, from Proto-Germanic *haitijaną.

From Middle High German hütte, from Old High German hutta (“hut, cottage”), possibly from Proto-Germanic *hudjǭ, though the word is originally exclusively High German. Further origin unknown. Some theories link it to Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewt- (“to deck; cover; covering; skin”). All related words in European languages are borrowings from Old High German. Compare Dutch hut, French hutte, English hut, etc.
Jahr (“year”) +‎ hundert (“one hundred”). Compare Dutch jaarhonderd.

From Middle High German kabel, which is borrowed via Middle Low German from Middle Dutch cabel (“thick rope”), itself from northern French câble. The contemporary sense is from English cable, which see for more.
From Middle High German kamîn, from Old High German kemîn, from Latin camīnus. Compare English chimney.
Klima +‎ Anlage

From Middle High German klopfen, from Old High German klophōn, clophōn, from Proto-West Germanic *kloppōn, from Proto-Germanic *kluppōną. Cognate with Dutch kloppen, English club. See also the informal doublet kloppen (“to thump, beat, fight”).
vocabList.usage: an die Tür klopfen ― to knock on the door

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German künec, from Old High German kuning (rarer kunig), from Proto-West Germanic *kuning, from Proto-Germanic *kuningaz.[1]
From Middle High German künigin, from Old High German chuningin, from Proto-West Germanic *kuningini, equivalent to König +‎ -in. Cognate with West Frisian keninginne.

From Middle High German kruoc, from Old High German kruog, from Proto-West Germanic *krōgu, from Proto-Germanic *krōguz. Immediate cognates are Middle Dutch croech, Old English crōg, of obscure origin. Possibly from a Proto-Indo-European root shared with Old Armenian կարաս (karas, “pitcher, large jar”), Ancient Greek κρωσσός (krōssós, “pitcher”), but the phonetics are problematic.  Also compare Old Irish croiccenn (“skin”).[1][2]
From Middle High German lecheln. By surface analysis, lachen +‎ -eln.
From Middle High German lecherlich. Equivalent to lachen +‎ -er- +‎ -lich.
leb +‎ -haft.
From Middle High German nennen, nemmen, nemnen, from Old High German nemnen, from Proto-West Germanic *namnijan, from Proto-Germanic *namnijaną.

Compound of neu (“new”) +‎ gierig (“greedy”), but originally neusgierig with an adverbial genitive. A Middle Low German formation that replaced older Middle High German niugerne. Compare Dutch nieuwsgierig and Norwegian Bokmål nysgjerrig.
vocabList.usage:
Ich bin besonders neugierig auf die Sitten und Gebräuche anderer Kulturen.
I am very curious and keen to discover the customs and traditions of other cultures.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German persōnlīcheit. By surface analysis, persönlich +‎ -keit. Cognate with Dutch persoonlijkheid.
Borrowed from Latin pupa. Sense of "pupa" borrowed from New Latin.
From Quadrat (“square”) + Meter (“metre”).
From rasieren (“to shave”) +‎ Apparat (“device”).
From Middle High German rīȥen, from Old High German rīȥan (“to scratch”), from a conflation of two similar verbs:.
From reißen (“to pull apart, tear”) +‎ Verschluss (“closure, shutter”).
Borrowed from English rowdy.
From Rücksicht (“consideration”) +‎ -s- +‎ -los.
Schminke +‎ -en
vocabList.usage:
Ich schminke mich immer zu Hause vor dem Spiegel.
I always put on my make-up at home in front of the mirror.

vocabList.etym: A nominal formation related to Schopf (“tuft, crown (of feathers)”), as they were originally covered with bundles of straw. Cognate with dialectal English shippon (“cow-shed”).[1]

Schwager +‎ -in.
Cognate with Hunsrik Schwehrin.
vocabList.usage:
Ist diese Schwägerin die Frau Ihres Bruders oder die Schwester Ihrer Frau?
Is this sister-in-law your brothers’s wife or your wife’s sister?

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German swanger, from Old High German swangar, from Proto-West Germanic *swangr (“heavy”), further origin unknown.[1] Cognate with Old English swangor, Dutch zwanger (“pregnant”), and Yiddish שוואַנגער (shvanger, “pregnant”); compare also Lithuanian sunkùs (“heavy; difficult”).
vocabList.usage:
Sie ist schwanger von ihrem Mann Peter mit ihrem dritten Kind.
She is pregnant from her husband Peter with her third child.

vocabList.etym: Expanded from earlier Schwieger (“mother-in-law”), from Old High German swigar, from Proto-Germanic *swegrō, from Proto-Indo-European *sweḱruh₂- (“woman's mother-in-law”) (compare *swéḱuros (“woman's father-in-law”)). By surface analysis, schwieger- +‎ Mutter.
schwieger- +‎ Vater.
From Middle High German sëlpstēnde +‎ -ig.

From Middle High German seltsām, seltzām, seltsæm, alteration (due to Middle High German -sam (“-some”)) of Middle High German seltsæn, seltsæne, from Old High German seltsāni. Cognate with Dutch zeldzaam and English seldom.
From spülen (“to rinse or wash”) +‎ Küche (“kitchen”).
stief- (“step-”) +‎ Mutter (“mother”)
From Middle High German strīt, from Old High German strīt, from Proto-West Germanic *strīd, from Proto-Germanic *strīdaz.
Sympathie +‎ -isch
From older Italian tastatura; compare tastiera. Analysable as Taste (“key, button”) +‎ -tur.

From Middle High German toup, toub, from Old High German toub, from Proto-West Germanic *daub, from Proto-Germanic *daubaz, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, be obscured”); cognate to English deaf, Swedish döv.
Teppich (“carpet”) +‎ Boden (“ground, floor”)
From Middle High German troum, Old High German troum, from Proto-West Germanic *draum, from Proto-Germanic *draumaz; akin to Low German Droom, Dutch droom, English dream, Danish drøm.
From Middle High German and Old High German troumen, from Proto-West Germanic *draumijan. Akin to Dutch dromen, English dream, and Swedish drömma.
ver- +‎ Antwort (“answer”) +‎ -ung.
vocabList.usage:
Diese Verantwortung kann dir niemand abnehmen.
Nobody can take this responsibility away from you.

vocabList.etym: Nominal of vergnügen.
vocabList.usage:
Es ist ein Vergnügen, Sie kennenzulernen.
It's a pleasure to meet you.

vocabList.etym: ver- +‎ größer +‎ -en
A conversion from the verb vertrauen (“to trust”) which has been used since the 1400s.
waschen +‎ Lappen

From Middle High German weinen, from Old High German weinōn (“to cry, lament, cry woe”), from Proto-Germanic *wainōną (“to cry, weep”), from Proto-Indo-European *wáy (“woe”). Related with Weh, English woe, which see. Cognate with Dutch wenen (“to weep, to cry”), Old English wānian (“to complain, lament”).
From Winter (“winter”) +‎ Garten (“garden”).
vocabList.usage:
Unsere Nachbarn haben ihren Balkon in einen Wintergarten umgewandelt.
Our neighbours converted their balcony into a conservatory.

vocabList.etym: From late Middle High German winzic, an intensification of wenig (“little, few”); further origin uncertain. First attested in the 14th century.

From Middle High German witewe, from Old High German wituwa, from Proto-West Germanic *widuwā, from Proto-Germanic *widuwǭ, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁widʰéwh₂ (“widow”). Germanic cognates include Dutch weduwe, Old Saxon widowa, Old English widuwe, whence English widow, which see.
From Middle High German witewære, witewer, witwer, from Old High German wituwo.

From Early New High German zuoval, a calque of Latin accidēns; see zufallen. Attested in the 15th century.[1]
Cognate with Dutch toeval.
From Middle High German acker, from Old High German ackar (“field”), from Proto-West Germanic *akr.
Borrowed from French allée.
From Middle High German bach, from Old High German bah, from Proto-West Germanic *baki. Cognate with English beach and English beck.
From Middle High German būwen, from Old High German būan, from Proto-West Germanic *būan, from Proto-Germanic *būaną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰúHt, the athematic root aorist of the root *bʰuH-.
vocabList.usage: ein Haus bauen ― to build a house

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German būre, gebūre, from Old High German būr (“peasant”), gibūr, gibūro. All these forms ultimately descend from Proto-West Germanic *būr, itself from Proto-Germanic *būraz (“inhabitant, dweller”). Compare English boor.
From compound Bauer (“farmer”) +‎ -n- +‎ Hof (“yard; enclosure”). Akin to Dutch boerenhof.

From Middle High German boum, from Old High German boum, from Proto-West Germanic *baum, from Proto-Germanic *baumaz. Akin to Dutch boom, Low German Boom, West Frisian beam, English beam. Plural umlaut by proportional analogy with terms like Gast (“guest”) to Gäste (“guests”).
vocabList.usage:
Bäume zählen zu den größten Lebensformen.
Trees are one of the biggest life forms.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German bërc, from Old High German bërg, itself from Proto-West Germanic *berg, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *bergaz.

From Middle High German blat, plat, from Old High German blat, from Proto-West Germanic *blad (“leaf”), from Proto-Germanic *bladą (“leaf”); akin to Low German Blatt, Dutch blad, English blade, Danish and Swedish blad. Indo-European cognates include Ancient Greek φύλλον (phúllon), Latin folium.

From Middle High German boden, bodem, from Old High German bodam, from Proto-West Germanic *bodm, from Proto-Germanic *budm-, a variant of *butmaz (whence English bottom, which see for more), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰudʰmḗn.
Bund +‎ es +‎ Straße
19th century, from Bürger (“citizen”) +‎ Steig (“footpath”). Introduced as a puristic alternative to then-predominant Trottoir (therefore unusual in Switzerland, like other purisms of that era).
vocabList.usage:
Auch auf dem Bürgersteig muss man immer die Augen auf halten.
You always have to keep your eyes open, even on the sidewalk.

vocabList.etym: From Bus (“bus”) +‎ (an)halten (“hold/stop”) +‎ Stelle (“place/location”).
Inherited from Middle High German dach, from Old High German dah, from Proto-West Germanic *þak, from Proto-Germanic *þaką, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *(s)teg-.

From Middle High German velt, from Old High German feld, from Proto-West Germanic *felþu, from Proto-Germanic *felþą, from Proto-Indo-European *pelh₂-. Cognates include Dutch veld and English field.[1]
From Middle High German vlach, from Old High German flah, from Proto-West Germanic *flak, from Proto-Germanic *flakaz.
From Middle High German vluz, from Old High German fluz, from Proto-West Germanic *fluti, from Proto-Germanic *flutiz, ultimately from the same root of fließen (“to flow”).
From Middle High German gebiet, gebiete (“jurisdiction; area of command”), from gebieten (“to command”). Compare Dutch gebied.
vocabList.usage:
Viele Bewohner hatten das bedrohte Gebiet verlassen müssen.
Many residents had to leave the threatened area.

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gebirge, from Old High German gibirgi; originally a collective noun equivalent to ge- +‎ Berg.
From Middle High German hecke, from Old High German hegga, from Proto-West Germanic *haggju, from Proto-Indo-European *kagʰyo-. Cognate with Dutch heg, English hedge.
From Middle High German hogil, diminutive of houc, from Old High German houg.
15th century, from Italian canale, from Latin canalis. The broadcasting sense is a semantic loan from English channel.
From Middle High German strāȥe, from Old High German strāȥa, from Proto-West Germanic *strātu (“street”), from Latin (via) strata.
vocabList.usage:
Das Kind überquerte die Straße.
The child crossed the street.

vocabList.etym: From Straße +‎ -n- +‎ Bahn.
From Middle High German tal, from Old High German tal. Cognate with Danish dal, Dutch dal, English dale, Swedish dal.

From Middle High German uover, ūver, ūber, possibly from northern Old High German *uofar, but usually considered a borrowing from Middle Low German ōver, ȫver, from Old Saxon *ōvar, *ōvir, from Proto-Germanic *ōferaz. Cognate with Dutch oever, Low German Över, English over (“shore, riverbank”). The native High German word for “shore” is Gestade.
From Middle High German walt, from Old High German wald, from Proto-West Germanic *walþu.
From Middle High German wonen, from Old High German wonēn, from Proto-West Germanic *wunēn, from Proto-Germanic *wunāną, from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”).

From Middle High German wonunge, from Old High German wonunga, from Proto-West Germanic *wunungu, equivalent to wohnen +‎ -ung. Related to Dutch woning (“house, residence”), English woning (“dwelling-place”). More at woning.
Ultimately from Ancient Greek ἀποθήκη (apothḗkē). Doublet of Bodega, Bottich, and Boutique.
From northern Middle High German becker, from Old High German beckeri, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *bakārijaz. By surface analysis, backen +‎ -er.
Learned borrowing from Latin bibliothēca, from Ancient Greek βῐβλῐοθήκη (bĭblĭothḗkē).
From Brief (“letter”) +‎ Kasten (“box”).
From Brief (“letter”) +‎ Marke (“mark/stamp”).
From Middle High German brucke, from Old High German brugga, brucca, from Proto-West Germanic *bruggju. The neurological sense “pons” is a semantic loan from Latin pōns.
From Middle High German buoch, from Old High German buoh, from Proto-West Germanic *bōk, from Proto-Germanic *bōks. Cognate with English book.

From Middle High German burc, from Old High German burg, from Proto-West Germanic *burg, from Proto-Germanic *burgz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰérǵʰ-s, a form of Proto-Indo-European *bʰerǵʰ- (“fortified elevation”).

15th-century alteration (see below) of older Thum, from Middle High German and Old High German tuom, from Proto-West Germanic *dōm (whence Old Dutch duom, Middle Low German dôm), from Medieval Latin domus (literally “house”). The use probably goes back to domus episcopatus/episcopalis (“house of the bishopric”).[1][2] An alternative theory derives it from domus ecclesiae (“church house”), after Ancient Greek οἶκος τῆς ἐκκλησίας (oîkos tês ekklēsías).[3]
From French droguerie.
ein- +‎ werfen
From Gemüse +‎ Händler.
From Middle High German gescheft, from Old High German giscaft, from Proto-West Germanic *gaskafti. Cognate with Yiddish געשעפֿט (gesheft).
Probably from early modern Dutch juwelier, though the word is first attested in German. Analyzable as Juwel +‎ -ier.
From Middle High German kappelle, kapelle, from Old High German kappella, kapella, from Late Latin and Vulgar Latin cappella (“chapel”).
Clipping of Kinematograph m. Originally also used a masculine noun (der Kino).
From Middle High German kirche, from Old High German kirihha, from Proto-West Germanic *kirikā.
vocabList.usage:
