From Middle High German gesellescaft, from Old High German giselliscaft. Equivalent to Geselle +‎ -schaft.
From viel +‎ -falt. Cognate with Middle English felefold, Dutch veelvoud. Compare Modern English manifold and manyfold.
From vorder- +‎ Grund.
From über +‎ siedeln (separable) or über- +‎ siedeln (inseparable).
From Middle High German strīchen, from Old High German strīhhan, from Proto-West Germanic *strīkan. Cognate with Dutch strijken, English strike.

vocabList.definition: public green area, site, park, garden
vocabList.etym: From anlegen (“to attach, apply, build, create, ...”).
From handeln, later specialized to its current meaning.
From herein- +‎ lassen.

vocabList.definition: to , to keep , to employ, to engage
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German scheftec (“active”), possibly under the influence of Low German bescheftich (“bustling, industrious”); see the related schaffen for more.

vocabList.definition: A league in which clubs from the entire country participate.
vocabList.etym: From Bund (“federation”) +‎ -es- +‎ Liga (“league”), thus “federal league”, in the sense of “nationwide league”.
From Middle High German gelegenheit. By surface analysis, gelegen +‎ -heit.
Stadt +‎ -isch

From Middle High German stōzen, from Old High German stōzan, from Proto-West Germanic *stautan, from Proto-Germanic *stautaną, from Proto-Indo-European *stówd-e-ti, an o-grade intensive formation from *(s)tewd- (“to hit, push”).

vocabList.definition:
to put down, to set down
 to place, to leave

 to put away

 to park, to leave

to put away from
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German abestellen. Equivalent to ab- +‎ stellen.
From Middle High German vorvar, from vorvaren (“to go ahead, to precede”).[1]
aus- +‎ wandern
erwarten +‎ -ung
einwandern +‎ -er
From minder +‎ -heit.

vocabList.definition: to pursue, to follow, to hunt
vocabList.etym: ver- +‎ folgen. A calque of Latin persequor or its Romance descendants.

From Middle Low German knap, probably related to Old Norse hneppr (“button”) and hneppa (“pinch”), all from Proto-Germanic *knappô, *knappa-, which is perhaps related to Proto-West Germanic *knappō (“knob, boy”) or Proto-Germanic *knuppaz (“lump, clod”), though the semantic gaps are non-trivial.[1] Cognate with Dutch knap, but of uncertain ultimate origin. Also compare Danish næppe (“hardly at all”).[2]

From Middle High German vellic, vellec, from Old High German fellīg (“staggering, dilapidated, inclined to fall, obliged to yield or pay”), equivalent to Fall +‎ -ig. Cognate with Middle Low German vellich, Middle Dutch vellich, vallich.
From Middle High German gesamt, gesament, from Old High German gisamanōt, from samanōn (“to gather, collect”), from Proto-West Germanic *samnōn, from Proto-Germanic *samnōną (“to bring together”).
Deverbal from  aufnehmen.
From kurz + Frist.
auf- +‎ führen
Early 19th century, from ur- +‎ Wald.
From begeistern +‎ -ung.
Serie +‎ Mörder

From Middle High German dræjen, dræhen, from Old High German drāen (akin to Old Saxon thrāian), from Proto-West Germanic *þrāan, from Proto-Germanic *þrēaną. Cognate with Bavarian drahn, Dutch draaien and English throw.
From Middle High German burse, from Old High German bursa, from Late Latin bursa.
innerlich +‎ ver- -en
From Middle High German bestān, bestēn, from Old High German bistān, from Proto-Germanic *bistandaną, *bistāną. Equivalent to be- +‎ stehen (“to stand, be on one's feet”).

vocabList.definition: to bear, to stand, to endure, to take, to suffer, to tolerate, to handle
vocabList.etym: er- +‎ tragen
From Medieval Latin rabiatus.

vocabList.definition: at the top of one's voice
vocabList.etym: Borrowed from German Low German luudhals. By surface analysis, laut (“loud”) +‎ Hals (“neck; throat”).
From Bavarian goschert
Uncertain. Kluge and Pfeifer put forward a possible relation to greinen (“to cry, whine”).
From Middle High German stetes, from Proto-Germanic *stēdi-; cognate with Dutch steeds. Synchronically analyzed as an adverbial formation  stet (“steady, constant”) +‎ -s; see there for more.
Obsolete perfect passive participle of erheben.

From Middle High German nüehtern, from Old High German nuohtarn, nuohturn, from Latin nocturnus (“nocturnal”). The word was probably originally used among monks in monasteries, with sense development "nocturnal" > "of dawn (the edge of night and day)" > "not having consumed any sustenance yet" > "sober". Compare Danish nøgtern, Hunsrik nichter, English nocturnal.

From Middle High German drücken, from Old High German drucchen, from Proto-West Germanic *þrukkijan. Doublet of  drucken (“to print”), which was originally a southern variant, later standardized in a specialized sense.
Fläche +‎ deckend
From an- +‎ werben.
einführen +‎ -ung

vocabList.definition: to form, to shape, to create
vocabList.etym: Gestalt +‎ -en.
From Middle High German verslahen, from Old High German firslahan, from Proto-West Germanic *fraslahan. By surface analysis, ver- +‎ schlagen. Cognate with Old English forslēan and Dutch verslaan.
From Middle High German belegen, from Old High German bileggen. By surface analysis, be- +‎ legen. Cognate with English belay.
einschränken +‎ -ung
From Middle High German iedoch, idoch, ēdoch, from Old High German iodoh, iothoh. Equivalent to je +‎ doch. Compare Dutch edoch.
Grund +‎ Lage

First attested in the 15th century as undersuochen. This form suggests it already existed in Middle High German. The existence of an unattested Old High German form *untarsuohhen is probable, compare Old Saxon undarsōkian (whence Low German ünnersöken), Old Dutch undersuoken (whence Dutch onderzoeken), and Old English undersecan (whence English underseek), all from Proto-West Germanic *undersōkijan (literally “to search under or between”). Equivalent to unter- +‎ suchen.
From Middle High German ervorschen, from Old High German irforskōn. Equivalent to er- +‎ forschen.
15th century, from Latin chīrūrgus, from Ancient Greek χειρουργός (kheirourgós).

From Sack (“sack”), which was used in the 19th century to refer to an unwaisted jacket; compare English sack coat. This name was due to the loose fitting, possibly reinforced by the idea of it being unpretentious and humble (compare Sack und Asche, English sackcloth). The later alteration of the form on the basis of Italian sacco was intended to have the opposite effect, namely to make it sound fashionable.
From Middle High German verstecken, from Old High German firstekken. Equivalent to ver- +‎ stecken. Cognate with Dutch versteken (“to hide”).
From Middle High German zwīvel, from Old High German zwīfal, from Proto-West Germanic *twīfl n, related to root of zwei. Doublet of  Doppel.

From Middle Low German gēgenēre, which is derived from a verb gēgenen (“to face, encounter”). Compare German begegnen. Ultimately pertaining to gegen (“against”). Cognate to Dutch jegener (“opponent”). Compare English gainer.
From Middle High German weren, from Old High German werien, from Proto-West Germanic *warjan, from Proto-Germanic *warjaną.

From Middle High German biderbe (also bederbe and shortened bider), from Old High German biderbi, piderpi, pidarpi, cognate with Bedarf.
The derogatory sense arises in the 19th century. The compound Biedermann in origin means "brave, honest or capable man", but today has a meaning of "boring person, petty bourgeios".
Back-formation from  wahnsinnig. Not related to Wahn.
From ewig +‎ -keit.

vocabList.definition: to acknowledge, to recognize, to accept
vocabList.etym: an- +‎ erkennen
an- +‎ nehmen
From Middle High German antrac.
From Middle High German armuot, armuote, from Old High German armuoti, from Proto-West Germanic *armōdī (“poverty”).[1][2]
Derived from zustehen, equivalent to zu- +‎ Stand.
Aufenthalt +‎ -s- +‎ Erlaubnis
Dauer +‎ -haft
From Middle High German vürhten, from Old High German furihtan. Synchronically analyzed as Furcht +‎ -en.

vocabList.definition:
to indicate, specify
to state, supply, give, report

 to show, represent

 to inform on, to betray, grass, rat out
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German anegeben. Equivalent to an- +‎ geben.
From Middle High German sulich, from Old High German sulīh, from Proto-Germanic *swalīkaz.
um- +‎ wandeln
From waschen +‎ Salon.
From the verb ablaufen.

From Middle High German brūwen, briuwen, from Old High German briuwan. The form shows the Central German development of Middle High German -iuw- → -ūw-, which is only sporadically reflected in the modern standard language (compare kauen).
From Gewächs +‎ Haus.
From Middle High German brīe, brī, from Old High German brīo, from Proto-West Germanic *brīw. Cognate with Yiddish ברײַ (bray).
Deverbal from  auftragen.
From Middle High German ursprunc, from Old High German ursprung. By surface analysis, ur- +‎ Sprung. Compare Dutch oorsprong.
Antrag +‎ Steller
From vergangen +‎ -heit.
From Middle High German vereinbæren. Analyzable as ver- +‎ ein +‎ -bar +‎ -en.
From zulassen (“to allow, to permit; to license”) +‎ -ung (“-ing”). Compare Dutch toelating.
From bescheiden (“to announce a decision”).
begegnen +‎ -ung

From Middle High German betriegen, from Old High German bitriogan, from Proto-West Germanic *bidreugan. Equivalent to be- +‎ trügen. The modern -ü- in this verb chiefly follows the development in the rhyming word lügen (“to lie”). It was reinforced by the noun Betrug and by the 2nd and 3rd person-singular forms (as in lügen itself, which compare).
heim- +‎ kehren
From Heirat (“marriage”) +‎ -s- +‎ Antrag (“application”).
ohne 'without' + hin 'thither, there'

From Middle High German welle, from Old High German wella, from Proto-West Germanic *wallijā, from Proto-Germanic *wallijǭ (“wave, swirl”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, coil”). Cognate to Old English wealca (“billow”), Albanian valë (“wave”).

From Middle High German gewalt, from Old High German giwalt, from Proto-West Germanic *gawald, from Proto-Germanic *gawaldą, from *ga- +‎ *waldą (“power, authority”). Cognate with Bavarian Gwoit, Yiddish געוואַלד (gevald), Dutch geweld, English wald.
From ansehen but can be implicitly constructed as an- +‎ Sicht.
From Middle High German nu, nū, nuo with a secondary final -n, already occasionally in Middle High German nuon, from Old High German nu, from Proto-West Germanic *nū.
From Middle High German entverren. Analysable as ent- +‎ fern + -en.

An originally Central and Low German verb, from Middle High German rāsen and Middle Low German rāsen, from Proto-West Germanic *rāsijan (“to race, rush”). Cognates include: Dutch razen, Old English rǣsan (“to hurry”), Old Norse rása (“to move quickly”).[1]
From Middle High German vernihten, from nihten, from niht. See nicht.
From Frau +‎ -en- +‎ Stimme.

vocabList.definition: to stand out, to be noticeable
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German ūfvallen, ūffallen, equivalent to auf- +‎ fallen. Cognate with Middle Low German upvallen.
From her +‎ vor.

vocabList.definition: to disappear, to vanish, to move out of view
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German verswinden, from Old High German firswintan, farswindan. Cognate with Middle Low German vorswinden, Dutch verzwinden. Equivalent to ver- +‎ schwinden.
From Middle High German spannen, from Old High German spannan, from Proto-Germanic *spannaną.

vocabList.definition: for there to be a lack
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German vælen, velen, valen, from Old French faillir, from Latin fallō. Cognate with English fail.
Borrowed from Latin fīliālis (“filial”) (DWDS), as branches of an organization are akin to "sons and daughters" of the organization.

From an onomatopoeic Middle High German rutzen, rützen (whence also the obsolete form rütschen), with change of -tz- to -tsch- as also in fletschen. Perhaps related to Old High German rūtezzen.[1] English rutch and rutsch derive from this term or its cognates in related languages.
From Middle High German bedürfen, bedurfen, from Old High German bidurfan (“need, require”). By surface analysis, be- +‎ dürfen.
From Middle High German getreide, contracted from getregede, from late Old High German gitregidi (“produce, income”), a collective derived from tragen (“to bear; to bear fruit”) (DWDS).
From Middle High German holz, from Old High German holz, from Proto-West Germanic *holt, from Proto-Germanic *hultą. Compare English holt (“thicket, copse; an otter's den”).
er- +‎ zeugen
From Middle High German trīben, from Old High German trīban, from Proto-West Germanic *drīban.

vocabList.definition: to come into being, to arise, to be produced
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German entstēn, entstān, from Old High German intstantan, intstantēn, intstantēn. Equivalent to ent- (“start”) +‎ stehen (“stand”).
ver- +‎ sorgen
Deverbal from  beitragen (“contribute”).

From Middle High German geringe, from Old High German giringi, ringi (“low, plain, simple, light, easy”), from Proto-Germanic *ringwaz (“small, light, quick”), of uncertain origin, though possibly from Proto-Indo-European *wrengʷʰ- (“to squeeze, wring”) and cognate with Proto-Germanic *wringaną (“to squeeze, wring”), Ancient Greek ῥίμφα (rhímpha, “fast, quickly”). Cognate with Yiddish גרינג (gring, “light, easy”) (DWDS).

From Low German and Middle Low German bedarf, the present stem of bedörven (“to need”), from Old Saxon bi- + tharvōn (“to need, lack, want”). Morphologically identical to the present singular of Middle High German and German bedürfen.

vocabList.definition: to build, to construct, to erect
vocabList.etym: auf- +‎ bauen
From aus- (“out”) +‎ Sicht (“sight”). Compare Dutch uitzicht.
From denken (“to think”) +‎ Mal (“symbol, sign”).
Borrowed from Italian soldato.

From Middle High German umbekomen (“to pass by, end, die”). Analysable as um- +‎ kommen. Cognate with Middle Dutch ommecomen (“to pass by, end, die”), whence modern Dutch omkomen. Compare also ums Leben kommen, and further umbringen, ums Leben bringen. Regarding the broader semantic use in both Middle High German and Middle Dutch, it is not certain that the short verbs are mere ellipses of the phrases with Leben, though they have without doubt been influenced by them.
From Middle High German slaht, from Old High German slahta, ultimately from the root of schlagen (“to strike, hit”). Compare Danish slag (“battle, strike”). Cognate of English slaughter.
er- +‎ weitern (“to extend, to expand”, obsolete, related to weit).
Univerbation of so +‎ wohl
un- +‎ eingeschränkt
From Middle High German vergenüegen (zufriedenstellen), derived from genug.
über- +‎ nehmen

From Middle High German enthalten, equivalent to ent- +‎ halten. Influenced by innehalten, einhalten (literally “to hold inside”). This is clearest in the sense “to contain”, compare Inhalt (“contents”); but it is possible even in the sense “to abstain”, compare mit etwas einhalten (“to stop”), sich einhalten (“to restrain oneself”). Cognate with Dutch onthouden (“to remember, withhold”) and inhouden (“to contain”), Middle Low German enthōlden, inhōlden.

From Middle High German beziehen, from Old High German biziohan, from Proto-West Germanic *biteuhan. Equivalent to be- +‎ ziehen. The sense “to refer” is probably influenced by Latin referre. Compare Dutch betrekken.
From Middle High German wërken, from Old High German werkōn, werhōn, from Proto-Germanic *werkōną. Cognate with Old Saxon werkōn, Old Dutch wirkon.
um- +‎ fassen
From hören +‎ Buch, literally “hear book”.
From einstufen +‎ -ung.
erhalten +‎ -lich
From the verb verhalten (“to behave”).

vocabList.definition: to abolish, to annul, to discontinue, to get rid of
vocabList.etym: ab- +‎ schaffen

vocabList.definition: to kill, to murder, to do away with
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German umbebringen, from Old High German umbibringan. Equivalent to um- +‎ bringen. Compare Dutch ombrengen.
Freizeit +‎ Beschäftigung
einstellen +‎ -ung
From gleichgültig +‎ -keit, since the second half of the 17th century.
Back-formation from  ausgleichen.

vocabList.definition: to freak out, to snap, to panic [auxiliary sein]
vocabList.etym: From durch- +‎ drehen.

vocabList.definition:
to keep, stick to, follow, observe, maintain, abide by, comply with
an appointment, promise etc.

a plan, course, speed etc.

a tradition, rule, decision etc.
vocabList.etym: From ein- +‎ halten, an alteration of innehalten, which used to have the same senses, but has since been restricted to “pause, wait”. Compare also enthalten.

vocabList.definition: to avoid, bypass, to go around
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German umbegēn, umbegān, from Old High German umbigēn, umbigān, from Proto-West Germanic *umbigān, from Proto-Germanic *umbigāną. Equivalent to um- +‎ gehen.
From Middle High German sorcveldic, sorcveltic, synchronically analyzable as Sorgfalt +‎ -ig.
From Middle High German ūfhalten. Equivalent to auf- +‎ halten. Cognates include Dutch ophouden and English uphold.
From Middle High German undersagen, from Old High German untarsagēn. Equivalent to unter- +‎ sagen.
From Middle High German kleben, from Old High German klebēn (“to stick”), from Proto-West Germanic *klibēn.

vocabList.definition: to determine, to ascertain, to establish, to find, to see
vocabList.etym: fest- +‎ stellen
Analysable as einschließen +‎ -lich.
Ausnahme +‎ Fall
From Middle High German diupstāle, compound of diep (“thief”) (modern Dieb) and stāle, deverbal noun from stëln (“to steal”) (modern stehlen), from Old High German stëlan.

From Middle High German vorsehen, from Old High German forasehan, from Proto-West Germanic *forēsehwan. Equivalent to vor- +‎ sehen. Cognate with Dutch voorzien, English foresee (from Old English foresēon).
From auf- +‎ stellen.
Wert +‎ Sache
auf- +‎ bewahren
From Middle High German haftunge, from Old High German haftunga. By surface analysis, haften (“to be liable, to stick”) +‎ -ung (“-ing”).
From Middle High German verschieben, from Old High German firskioban. Equivalent to ver- +‎ schieben.

From Middle High German gebærde, from Old High German gibārida, gibāridī (“demeanor, behavior, character”), from Proto-Germanic *gabērijaną, *gabarjaną (“to conduct oneself, behave”); see the related *gaberaną (“to bear, beget”) for more. Cognate with dialectal German Bärde, German Low German Gebarr, Dutch gebaarde, Middle English bærde, beard, beorde (“conduct, bearing”).

vocabList.definition: to fill with enthusiasm, to enthuse, to thrill
vocabList.etym: From be- +‎ Geist +‎ -ern.
verhalten +‎ -nis
verzeichnen +‎ -nis.
From Middle High German schrīten, from Old High German skrītan, from Proto-West Germanic *skrīþan (“to step; stride”).
ob- +‎ Acht
los- +‎ gehen; cognate with Hunsrik losgehn
From gestalt(en) (“to form, shape”) +‎ -ung.
From Middle High German esel, from Old High German esil, from late Proto-West Germanic *asil, which is borrowed from Late Latin asellus.
From Middle High German dringen, from Old High German dringan. Akin to drängen and Drang. Cognate with dialectal English thring and, more distantly, with English throng.
From Middle High German bezirc, from be- + zirc, from Latin circus, itself from Ancient Greek κίρκος (kírkos, “circle, ring”).
zutragen +‎ -lich.
From ankommen.

vocabList.definition: to put off, drive off, scare off
vocabList.etym: 20th century, from ver- +‎ graulen (“to be scared”, rare or regional). The latter is from earlier graueln, a variant of (also rare) gräueln, from Middle High German griuweln, grūweln, whence the noun Gräuel (“horror”). The form with -ūw- (modern -au-) probably shows the same Central German development as in brauen, kauen. The change from -eln to -len is unremarkable (in fact, many speakers merge these entirely).
Zusatz +‎ -lich
From Behinderter +‎ -n- +‎ feindlich.
aus +‎ -kunft, a form of kommen.
Zufall (“chance, coincidence, randomness”) +‎ -ig
From Middle High German almehlich. By surface analysis, all- +‎ mählich (“slow”), from Proto-Germanic *makaz; related to Old Norse makligr.

vocabList.definition: to scrutinize, to examine, to inspect, to look over, to eye
vocabList.etym: From the noun Muster.
Borrowed from French cravate. Compare English cravat and Spanish corbata. Doublet of  Kroate (“Croat”).
From ab- +‎ driften.
From be- +‎ Mühe +‎ -en. Compare Dutch bemoeien.
16th century, alteration of earlier gewähnen, from Middle High German gewähenen, gewahen, from Old High German giwahanen, giwahan, from Proto-West Germanic *gawahwan (“to say, mention”).

15th century, from Mahl (“meal”) +‎ Zeit (“time”). The word Mahl (a spelling variant of Mal) originally meant "mealtime", but was transferred to the meal itself. The compound then assumed the sense "mealtime", but ultimately underwent the same semantic development yet again. Compare Dutch maaltijd, English mealtide, Danish måltid, Icelandic máltíð.
vor- +‎ wiegen (“weigh”)
er- +‎ ganz
From Middle High German âventiure, borrowed from Old French aventure and like the latter originally feminine. The neuter gender is from Middle Low German.
From Riese (“giant”) +‎ -ig.
aus- +‎ steigen
rum- +‎ laufen
üben +‎ -lich
Reihe +‎ -n- +‎ Haus

From Middle High German rîter, rîtære, from Old High German rîtari. Not of Proto-Germanic age, but an OHG formation from the verb rītan "to ride" (Anglo-Saxon rîdere and Old Icelandic ríðari are loans from OHG).
From Middle High German schetzen (Duden), synchronically analyzable as a verbal formation from Schatz (“treasure”) (DWDS).
17th century, from schlecht +‎ hin. The first component here preserves the older sense “plain, simple”, otherwise now restricted to the variant schlicht (see there).

vocabList.definition: sometimes, occasionally, from time to time, now and then

vocabList.etym: auflösen +‎ -ung. Compare Dutch oplossing.

vocabList.definition: to give away, to throw away
vocabList.etym: ver- +‎ schenken

From bestecken (“to provide a thing by inserting it into another thing”), from be- +‎ stecken. Originally referred to a case into which a set of tools was put, later shifting to refer to the tools themselves.
From Middle High German ūȥschuȥ, synchronically analyzed as a deverbal from  ausschießen (“to stand out”); see aus- (“out-”) +‎ schießen (“to shoot”) for more.

vocabList.definition: to accept, to promise to come
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German zuosagen. Equivalent to zu- +‎ sagen.
From Middle High German geslechte, from Old High German gislahti, a collective formation from slahta, from Proto-Germanic *slahtō, related to *slahaną (“to strike, hit”).[1]
From Middle High German gestaten, Old High German gistatōn,[1] related to Status (“status”); see there for more.[2]

From two separate but related verbs. From Middle High German verwīzen, Old High German firwīzan, from Proto-West Germanic *frawītan, from Proto-Germanic *frawītaną and the second verb from Middle High German verwīsen, from unattested Old High German *firwīsan, from Proto-West Germanic *frawīsijan, from Proto-Germanic *frawīsijaną.  By surface analysis, ver- +‎ weisen.
From Middle High German gelende, from Old High German gilenti; originally a collective noun equivalent to ge- +‎ Land.
From Middle High German erahten, from Old High German irahtōn. Equivalent to er- +‎ achten.
Literally, “to tell information”.

vocabList.definition: to handle, to cope with, to get over, to overcome
vocabList.etym: From be- + waltig +‎ -en, in which waltig is an obsolete variant of gewaltig.[1]

From Middle High German überwinden, from Old High German ubarwintan, an originally Upper German form besides Central German überwinnen, ubarwinnan. This latter is from Proto-West Germanic *ubarwinnan. Cognate with Dutch overwinnen, English overwin. Equivalent to über- + winnen (“to win”, simplex of gewinnen). The form with -nd- is analysable as über- +‎ winden (“to wind, twist”). It is uncertain whether this is a mere phonetic alteration of the nn-form or an actual derivation from the verb. For the latter possibility compare isolated Middle High German uses like anewinden (“to attack”), widerwinden (“to repulse”).
From Middle High German vūl, from Old High German fūl, from Proto-West Germanic *fūl, from Proto-Germanic *fūlaz, from Proto-Indo-European *puH-lo-s (“rotten, putrid”).

From Middle High German (ge)vancnisse, (ge)vencnisse (“capture, captivity”), since 15th century for the place of the captivity, equivalent to gefangen (“caught”) +‎ -nis. More at fangen (“to catch”). Cognate with Dutch gevangenis.
ein- +‎ sitzen
From ausschenken. Cognate with German Low German Utschank.
an- +‎ fassen
From Middle High German īngān, from Old High German ingān, from Proto-West Germanic *ingān. Analyzable as ein- +‎ gehen.
Univerbation of an +‎ Hand.
einig +‎ -keit
Middle High German loube, from Old High German louba, from Proto-West Germanic *laubijā.

vocabList.definition: to move in a quiet and inconspicuous manner, hence often slowly and/or ducked: to crawl, to sneak, to steal, to prowl, to creep, to slither
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German slīchen, from Old High German slīhhan. Compare English slink.
From Middle High German fūst, vūst, voust, from Old High German fūst.
From Middle High German stoc, from Old High German stoc, from Proto-West Germanic *stokk.

Originally the same word as Teich (“pond”). The sense “dike” spread via Low German, for which reason the form Deich is most often regarded as an artificial adaptation of Middle Low German dīk (“dike”) to the phonetic system of standard German. However, Deich is also the form natively developed in West Central German and it does mean “dike, dam, weir system” in most dialects of the Rhineland, particularly along the Lower Rhine. The supposition of an artificial adaptation is therefore possible but not inevitable. Cognate to Dutch dijk and West Frisian dyk.

From Middle High German rūch, from Old High German rūh, from Proto-Germanic *rūhwaz. Though etymologically justified, the silent h was abolished in 1996 because rauh was the only word in which it was used after the diphthong -au-. Cognate with Dutch ruig and ruw, English rough (which see).

Although the noun must underlie the adjective, the former is not attested again (after Notker) before the 15th century; it remained rare until ca. 1650.  Compare Dutch voorzicht, English foresight.

From Middle High German spinne, from Old High German spinna. Ultimately an agent noun from the verb from which spinnen (“to spin”) is derived. Cognate with Dutch spin (“spider”), archaic English spinner (“spider”).

Borrowed from Middle Low German vlīse, from Proto-Germanic *flīsō (“split chip”), a nasalized dental extension of Proto-Indo-European *(s)pley- (“to split, splice”), whence also Proto-Germanic *splītaną (“to split”). Cognate with Swedish flis (“wood chips”) (DWDS).
From Speicher (“storehouse”).
